<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fears of Instability Overstated: Indonesian Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, February 23 (Xinhua) -- An Indonesian official said
here Wednesday that investors' fears of his country's instability
are overstated.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian Coordinating Minister for Economy, Finance and
Industry Kwik Kian Gie made the remarks while delivering an
address at the Third Annual Presidents Forum which opened here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing an audience of some 200 business leaders from
Southeast Asia, Gie said the chaotic days of May 1998 have made
many investors have second thoughts about whether it is sensible
to invest in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that fears over instability today are overstated for
a number of reasons," he said.
</P>
<P>
First, Gie said, in the past two years there has been a sea
change in the politics of governance in the country, which has
created a democratic dialogue that continues to this day in a
social climate that is remarkably calm.
</P>
<P>
He said the relatively peaceful elections last June and the
smooth election of the new president and vice president have given
the people hope for a new and more prosperous era under the
guidance of the new government.
</P>
<P>
The improving state of the Indonesian economy despite
pessimistic projections made by observers in mid-1998, he said, is
the second reason that fears of instability are overstated.
</P>
<P>
Since the election of the new government, the Indonesian rupiah
has stabilized which in turn has brought about positive impacts on
the economy such as a low inflation of 2 percent for 1999.
</P>
<P>
Gross domestic product (GDP) has increased substantially since
the fourth quarter of 1998, with the GDP in the fourth quarter of
1999 5.7 percent higher than the same period in 1998, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said, a recovery in exports is emerging with non-
oil exports from August to December 1999 5.5 percent higher than
the same period in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Having laid the foundation of macroeconomic stability,Gie said,
the Indonesian government is now working to address the other
major issues facing the economy, especially in the area of bank
recapitalization and corporate restructuring.
</P>
<P>
At the end of his speech, the minister called on foreign
investors to go to Indonesia and take part in the recovery which
has begun there as the latest economic data suggest.
</P>
<P>
The Presidents Forum is organized by the Business Week to
examine the best business practices that will allow companies to
embark on growth strategies as the region begins its recovery
process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
