<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Talks on Nepal's Entry to WTO to Begin in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, February 23 (Xinhua) -- Formal talks on accession of
Nepal to the World Trade Organization (WTO) will begin in May this
year, according to the Ministry of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
Nepal will complete all formalities for membership within five
to six months, Commerce Minister Ram Krishna Tamrakar said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed confidence that it will not be long before
Nepal is granted the accession.
</P>
<P>
Following the stalemate over trade and transit agreements
between Nepal and India at the end of the 1980s, Nepal began
seeking membership in the General Agreement of Trade and Tariff,
which was later transformed into the WTO. With accession to the
WTO, landlocked Nepal can be guaranteed transit facilities.
</P>
<P>
The Himalayan kingdom, which adopted a market-oriented liberal
economic policy in the early 1990s, has been taking part in WTO
meetings as an observer since the organization's inception.
</P>
</TEXT>
