<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mongolia Urges Russia to Restore Power Supply to Its Western Provinces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, February 23 (Xinhua) -- Mongolian Prime Minister R.
Amarjargal has requested Russia to immediately restore power
supply to his country's three western provinces.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to Russian Acting President and Prime Minister V.
Putin, Amarjargal emphasized that the Mongolian side should not be
blamed for the sudden interruption of power supply to the three
provinces that import energy from Russia, because Mongolia has
already forwarded the payment for the power supply.
</P>
<P>
The interruption was caused by problems in relations between
two Russian organizations, he said.
</P>
<P>
Amarjargal also said that the power cut in the three provinces
since February 16 has caused tremendous difficulties to residents,
heating systems, hospitals, schools and other organizations there.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister mentioned in the letter that the Mongolian
Energy Board has been negotiating with relevant Russian
organizations to conclude new agreements on power supply.
</P>
<P>
However, under Russian law, the agreements would not come into
force until two to three weeks after their conclusion, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
