<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at GMT 1630, February 23 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. Senator John McCain defeated Texas Governor
George W. Bush in the primaries in Michigan and Arizona on Tuesday
night, regaining momentum in the race for the Republican
presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
In Michigan, with 37 percent of 5,637 precincts reporting,
McCain had 50 percent of the vote while Bush had 44 percent.
</P>
<P>
In Arizona, with 2 percent of 385 precincts reporting, McCain
won 53 percent of the vote and was declared winner. Bush got 44
percent. (BC-US-Primary)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel and the Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
have arrested dozens of Palestinians in a crackdown on terrorism
over the past weeks, the Ha'aretz daily reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the Israel Defense Forces (IDF) said in a
statement that the arrested were members of the Islamic militant
group Hamas, which is opposed to the peace process between Israel
and the Palestinians.  (BC-Israel-Palestinians-Terror Cell)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Former Russian President Boris Yeltsin on Wednesday
praised Acting President Vladimir Putin and urged Russians to vote
for him in the upcoming presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
"Putin is on the right road and follows it firmly," Yeltsin
told reporters during a visit to the residence of Patriarch Alexy
II of Moscow and All Russia, the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
(BC-Yeltsin-Putin)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian Acting President Vladimir Putin met Wednesday
with visiting British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook and the two
sides agreed to intensify economic and political ties and
cooperation in combating international terrorism.
</P>
<P>
In what was described as an "involved and open" discussion that
last one hour and a half, Putin told Cook that Russia's operation
against rebels in the breakaway republic of Chechnya "has largely
been transferred to a political level."(BC-Russia-Britain-Ties)
</P>
</TEXT>
