<HEADLINE> Tom.com Mania Through Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 23 (Xinhua) -- The Internet frenzy whirled
around Hong Kong with tens of thousands of people queuing up
outside of bank branches Wednesday to submit application forms for
shares in the Internet company -- tom.com, which is due to be
listed on the Growth Enterprise Market (GEM) here on March 1.
</P>
<P>
The overwhelming response to tom.com Ltd. caused chaos at
several of the 10 HSBC (Hong Kong and Shanghai Banking Corporation
Limited) branches charged with dealing with the initial public
offering (IPO) and extra policemen had to be deployed to maintain
order.
</P>
<P>
The lobby of the HSBC headquarters at Central was jammed with
people while about 20,000 people lined up outside the branch at
Kwun Tong and 50,000 people waited at the branch in Mong Kok.
</P>
<P>
Bank staff used bags to collect the forms after the boxes
provided were filled up.
</P>
<P>
The noon deadline for submitting the application forms was
finally extended by nearly two hours to clear the backlog.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the IPO for tom.com, which is 57 percent
owned by Hutchison Whampoa and Cheung Kong (Holdings) Ltd., both
controlled by Hong Kong tycoon Li Ka-shing, could be over-
subscribed for up to 2,000 times.
</P>
<P>
A total of 42.8 million shares at 1.78 Hong Kong dollars, one-
tenth of the total shares issued, have been offered to the public
with almost 1.5 million application forms distributed, equivalent
to one out of every four Hong Kong people snapping up one form.
</P>
<P>
The shares of the Internet content provider are expected to
soar to between 5 and 10 HK dollars when they make their debut on
the GEM, Hong Kong's equivalent of the U.S. Nasdaq exchange.
</P>
<P>
Tom.com plans to raise approximately 630 million to 760 million
HK dollars (80.8 million to 97.4 million U.S. dollars) through the
issue.
</P>
<P>
In a separate development, Hong Kong.com, the Hong Kong unit of
China.com, plans to raise about 832 million HK dollars (106.7
million U.S. dollars) by issuing 640 million shares at a price of
between 1 and 1.3 HK dollars.
</P>
<P>
The issuing of the shares of Hong Kong.com, due to be listed on
the GEM on March 14, will expire on March 7.
</P>
<P>
Analysts warned that there was high risk in investment and
advised investors to be cautious.
</P>
<P>
"A highly over-subscribed initial public offering is often
followed by a shocking diminution of shareholder value and a very
weak share price," said Stephen Vines, a financial analyst.
</P>
<P>
Secretary for Financial Services Rafael Hui Si-yan of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region has warned Internet and
technology firms, in particular, that the companies which provide
false information on the stock market would be severely penalized.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
