<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drug Abuse Increasing in South Asia: UN Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, February 23 (Xinhua) -- The International Narcotic
Control Board of the United Nations warned Wednesday that drug
abuse has been on the rise in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
The board, in a report launched across the world Wednesday,
said, "There seems to be millions of drugs abusers in the region."
</P>
<P>
While cannabis and opium have traditionally been the main drugs
of the abuse, the abuse of heroin and synthetic drugs is rapidly
increasing, it said.
</P>
<P>
The number is particularly high along the main trafficking
routes and in major drug trafficking areas such as the
southwestern border area of Bangladesh and India.
</P>
<P>
Because of the increasing abuse of heroin by injection and
sharing of needles, the number of HIV-AIDS cases is rising in most
countries in South Asia, though the preferred mode of
administering heroin continues to be inhalation, it noted.
</P>
<P>
Because of proximity of South Asia to the world's two main
opiate-producing countries Afghanistan and Myanmar, drug
trafficking and drug abuse in the region have been mainly transit-
related, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Approximately 75 percent of the world production of opium takes
place in Afghanistan with cultivation spreading to new areas, the
report noted, saying that in 1999 production reached a record
level of 4,600 tons.
</P>
<P>
The report said a large quantity of heroin has been smuggled
out of Afghanistan and out of Myanmar and into countries in South
Asia, mainly to be shipped further to illicit markets in Europe
and North America, but also to be abused locally.
</P>
<P>
It said the supply of illicit opiate from Southwest Asia
continues and may increase as a result of record opium harvest in
Afghanistan. Trafficking in raw opium and heroin from northwestern
Myanmar has been on the rise for the past few years.
</P>
<P>
The illicit cultivation of opium poppy and the production of
opiates are also taking place in various parts of India and Nepal,
it said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the board noted with satisfaction that a number of
countries in South Asia are devoting increased attention to the
prevention of the drug abuse and the treatment and rehabilitation
of drug addicts and to the involvement of non-governmental
organizations in those activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000224.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua Photo List for February 23 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Beijing, February 23, Xinhua -- Following is the photo list for
February 23 released by Xinhua:
</P>
<P>
1. Bai Guangyuan, 11, of Beijing, has a go game on-line with an
unidentified amateur chess player in the Republic of Korea on
Wednesday. All together six players from the two countries
participated in the international go competition on-line.
</P>
<P>
2. The first pair of test-tube boy-and-girl twin of Shandong
Province lie in the thermos-bin in the Hospital affiliated to the
Shandong Medical University on Wednesday in Jinan, capital of east
China's Shandong Province. The twin were born on Monday and weigh
2.7 kg and 2.4 kg respectively. Their parents are peasants from
Zhangqiu city.
</P>
<P>
3. Three photographers take photos at the Hukou waterfall of
the Yellow River in Jixian County in Shanxi province. The Hukou
waterfall is one of the largest waterfalls in China and was frozen
since last winter because of low temperature and great amount of
ice blocks from upper reaches. The Hukou waterfall now roars as
usual.
</P>
<P>
4. Three lamas enjoy a beautiful snow scene Wednesday in Xining,
capital of west China's Qinghai Province. The snowfall helps ease
the drought of Qinghai Province.
</P>
<P>
5. Female workers of private-owned Zhiyuan Industrial Group
check woven plastic bags. The yearly output of this company
reached almost 20 million yuan RMB. These years the private
economy in southwest China's Sichuan Province has boomed. Some 1.
73 million individual businesses households and 47,000 private
enterprises turned in 4.48 billion yuan RMB in tax to the state in
1999 in Sichuan.
</P>
<P>
6. The bamboo forest of the Tianlin County of Guangxi Zhuang
Autonomous Region. In order to protect the forest, Guangxi planted
trees and bamboos on around 230 mu hilly land in 1999, doubled the
planted area of 1998.
</P>
<P>
7. The night view of the Three Gorges Water Conservancy
construction base of the Yangtze River. Modern equipment and
facilities are used on the construction base in order to ensure
the quality of the project. The stone smashing system, shown in
the picture, can process 2,175 tons per hour. It is the largest
stone smashing system in the world.
</P>
<P>
8. Wubingya Wensa, 70, solicits opinions regarding religious
work in the ethnic minority areas from two monks before leaving
for Beijing. Wensa, of the Dai ethnic origin, is a senior monk of
the Hansha Temple in Yunnan Province and a member of the National
Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference (CPPCC). He is to attend the CPPCC meeting in Beijing.
</P>
