<HEADLINE> Coca-Cola Company to Create 10,000 Jobs in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, February 23 (Xinhua) -- Leading beverage company
Coca-Cola Wednesday said it would reinvest gains from the South
African government's introduction of excise duty reduction to
create about 10,000 new jobs in the country during the next 12
months.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Wednesday, South African Finance Minister Trevor
Manuel announced a reduction in excise tax on soft drinks and
mineral waters by one-third, from 12 cents a litre to eight cents
a litre.
</P>
<P>
Coca-Cola Southern Africa president Doug Jackson applauded the
move.
</P>
<P>
"We are very excited about the excise tax reduction, and we
plan to leverage the uniqueness of the Coca-Cola system to create
thousands of retail outlets which will stimulate and sustain
approximately 10,000 new jobs," Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
According to Jackson, the details of the proposed job creation
program will be finalized over the next month by the managing
boards of Coca-Cola's five South African bottlers: Amalgamated
Beverage Industries, Coca-Cola SABCO, Fortune Beverages, TJC
Holdings and Peninsula Beverages.
</P>
<P>
It is anticipated that the majority of these new jobs will be
generated from Coca-Cola's micro-enterprise retail sector.
</P>
<P>
This sector currently accounts for 50 percent of the 180,000
jobs directly attributable to the Coca-Cola system in South
Africa, Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
