<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Government Deviates From Targets: IMF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) team said here on Thursday that it noted large deviations by
the Zimbabwean government from programed targets in the budgetary
and monetary areas.
</P>
<P>
The team, led by Assistant Director in the African Department
Paulo Neuhaus, said in a statement that the deviation had resulted
in inflation souring to about 57 percent.
</P>
<P>
"The mission advised the authorities to take steps to
strengthen significantly fiscal and monetary policies and to
restore equilibrium in the exchange market," statement said.
</P>
<P>
During its stay in Harare, the team had held talks with
Zimbabwe's Finance Minister Herbert Murerwa, Reserve Bank Governor
Leonard Tsumba and other senior government officials.
</P>
<P>
The team said there is need for the Zimbabwean government to
control budgetary expenditures by adhering to the Public Finance
Management System, which was established to control the
government's commitments and cash spending.
</P>
<P>
The meeting between the Zimbabwean government and the IMF was
one of a series of negotiations to secure support funds to
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The IMF has been urging the Zimbabwean government to show
positive moves to comply with its demands which include cutting
down on government spending.
</P>
<P>
However, the Zimbabwean government has been accusing the IMF of
having a hidden agenda, failing to appreciate some changes it has
made.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's economy is currently plagued by an inflation of
about 57 percent, an interest rate above 55 percent and shortages
of essentials such as foreign currency and fuel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
