<DOCNO> XIE20000224.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Launches Strategy Against AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Uganda AIDS Commission (UAC),
the country's top anti-AIDS coordinating body, on Thursday
launched a five-year national strategy in a bid to further cut
infection rate and eventually eliminate the killer disease from
its land.
</P>
<P>
The 69-page report, named The National Strategic Framework for
HIV/AIDS Activities in Uganda 2000-2005, is published and being
discussed at a two- day workshop by experts, officials and
representatives from U.N. agencies in Entebbe, near the capital
Kampala.
</P>
<P>
The framework is aimed at reducing HIV infection rate by 25
percent by the year 2005, mitigating the health and socio-economic
effects of HIV/ AIDS at the individual, household and community
levels as well as strengthening the national capacity to respond
to the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
UAC Director Kihumuro Apuuli said in the opening remarks that
Uganda's current HIV infection rate of 10 percent, though much
lower than that of over 25 percent a few years ago, is still
unacceptably high.
</P>
<P>
AIDS is hindering social and economic development of the
country by destroying its most productive labor force. People aged
15-49, the most sexually active age group and the bulk of the
labor force, are having the highest rate of infection, he added.
</P>
<P>
The framework recommends some key priority areas in the years
to come, including strengthening of implementation and
coordination, intensifying monitoring and evaluating efforts and
information sharing. A more harmonized, coordinated fight against
the epidemic is crucial to the final elimination of the disease,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
Since the first case of AIDS was reported in the country in
1982, more than 500,000 people have died of it and a total of 1.9
million children have become AIDS orphans.
</P>
<P>
UAC has achieved commendable results since its establishment in
1992, with Uganda being the only African country where the HIV
infection rate is steadily declining. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000224.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Urged to Shift Debt Relief to Poverty Reduction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Jubilee 2000-Zambia on Thursday
called on the government to create a mechanism to assure that
resources that become available because of debt relief are
directed toward poverty reduction program.
</P>
<P>
Jubilee 2000-Zambia, part of a worldwide campaign for the total
 cancellation of the debt of poor countries, made the appeal in a
statement released after a meeting in the capital Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
Zambia's total external debt stands at approximately 6.5
billion U.S. dollars now, according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
Over the past decade, Zambia has been paying debt service of
approximately 200 million dollars annually. This figure is
substantially higher than total social sector spending in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 70 to 80 percent of Zambians live in poverty while
the country continues to pay enormous sums for debt servicing.
</P>
<P>
It now appears that Zambia will soon be receiving some
significant debt relief, both from multi-lateral and bilateral
creditors.
</P>
<P>
But the most serious question being raised both by lender
institutions and nations and by citizens in Zambia is whether the
new resources to be made available will go to effective poverty
eradication programs in the country.
</P>
<P>
Efforts will now be made to put the proposal into the public
forum for further discussion and eventual implementation, so that
debt relief for Zambia will soon mean realistic steps toward
poverty eradication, it says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
