<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Declares State of Disaster in 3 Provinces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe has declared a state
of disaster in the three provinces of Manicaland, Masvingo and
Matabeleland South following the catastrophic effects of cyclone
Eline.
</P>
<P>
The death toll has risen to five and the damage caused is
estimated at millions of U.S. dollars, Local Government and
National Housing Minister John Nkomo told a news conference on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He said that an international appeal for aid has been launched
for the thousands of people left homeless and without food.
</P>
<P>
"Local resources have been channeled to affected areas, but
these are inadequate to bring the situation to normalcy," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the damage caused by the effects of the cyclone, now
downgraded to a depression, has amounted to millions of U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe is a member of Civil Protection International and
therefore qualified to approach individual countries for help, he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said the government is working on the necessary paperwork to
put through a formal appeal for aid to the United Nations
agencies.
</P>
<P>
"We have to proceed via a declaration of disaster and then we
will be contacting the U.N. agencies because they need information
on the exact areas that are affected," he said.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 250,000 people were said to have been rendered
homeless and would need food, temporary shelter, blankets and
water purifying aids.
</P>
<P>
"We are fearful about cholera and malaria and the people are
also exposed to snake attacks because the snakes have also moved
to high ground," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said some government officials would on Friday make an
aerial assessment of the damage that saw homes and granaries
being washed away.
</P>
<P>
The storms and floods wreaked havoc on infrastructure such as
roads, bridges, telecommunications and power lines, cutting off
communication links between the affected areas and command posts.
</P>
</TEXT>
