<HEADLINE> Detained Kurdish Mayors Arraigned in Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The three Kurdish mayors from a
pro-Kurdish party, taken into custody five days ago, were arraigned
early Thursday, the Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
They were interrogated for nearly 11 hours at the Diyarbakir
State Security Court (DGM) in the day and then transferred to the
DGM Alternate Judgeship.
</P>
<P>
No date has been set for their trial.
</P>
<P>
The three defendants were detained on charges of aiding and
abetting the outlawed Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK), which had
been fighting since 1984 for an independent Kurdish state in
southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The DGM will request jail terms of two to four and a half years
for the defendants.
</P>
<P>
The Emergency Rule Regional Governorship (OHAL), in charge of
security and stability affairs in Turkey's restive Kurds-populated
southeast, detained Feridun Celik, mayor of Turkey's biggest
Kurdish city Diyarbakir, Feyzullah Karaaslan of Bingol and Selim
Ozalp of Siirt on Saturday on charges of colluding with PKK.
</P>
<P>
The three are from the People's Democratic Party (HADEP), the
only legal pro-Kurdish party in Turkey which is already at the risk
of being banned for its alleged links with the PKK.
</P>
<P>
They were detained shortly after meeting with European officials
during which Kurdish rights were discussed.
</P>
<P>
The OHAL accused that the three mayors gave secret support for
PKK, attended meetings of the terrorist group, got instruction from
PKK and transferred some of their financial sources to the PKK.
</P>
<P>
In response to the call of detente by Ocalan from jail, the PKK
has announced to lay down arms and withdraw from Turkey. But the
Turkish government dismissed the PKK announcement as a plot.
</P>
<P>
In another development, a Turkish court sentenced 18 members of
HADEP, including its current and former presidents, to more than
three years' imprisonment for staging a hunger strike in support of
the doomed PKK leader Abdullah Ocalan. 
</P>
