<HEADLINE> No U.S. Pressure to Raise Oil Output: Kuwaiti Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Kuwaiti Oil Minister Sheikh
Saud Nasser Al-Sabah said Thursday that Kuwait and other oil
producing countries were not under U.S. pressure to increase output
to cool off soaring oil prices.
</P>
<P>
Saud said at a press conference with visiting U.S. Energy
Secretary Bill Richardson that the U.S. official has come to hold
talks on the situation in the world oil market.
</P>
<P>
"There was no direct or indirect pressure from Washington on
Kuwait," Saud said.
</P>
<P>
On a question about Kuwait's policy on oil production, the
official said this is not a Kuwaiti concern but is relevant to the
general policy of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
(OPEC).
</P>
<P>
Any output changes would be decided during the OPEC meeting by
the end of next month, Saud added.
</P>
<P>
The one-year output squeeze agreement reached by OPEC members
last March expires in March this year. OPEC ministers will meet in
Vienna on March 27 to decide whether or not to release more
supplies to replenish dwindling fuel stockpiles and bring down the
high oil prices.
</P>
<P>
The prices for benchmark North Sea Brent crude have recently
surged to a nine-year high of nearly 29 U.S. dollars a barrel
before standing firmly above the 26-dollar level.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Richardson, who arrived here earlier in the day on
a regional tour which will also take him to Saudi Arabia, said the
reason behind his trip is to explain the U.S. point of view over
the oil prices in the international market.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.S. holds that oil price should be subject to
supply and demand in order not to hurt the global economy. U.S.
officials, including President Bill Clinton, have expressed concern
over the high oil price, fearing it may lead to world-wide
inflation.
</P>
<P>
Oil business sources said in earlier press reports that
Richardson's visit to the two U.S. allies in the oil-rich Gulf was
aimed at gathering support from oil producing countries to loose
their output curbs to balance the market.
</P>
<P>
Richardson had said that he did not want to release the U.S.
strategic crude reserves on to the world market, but that oil
prices at 30 dollars a barrel were too high. 
</P>
</TEXT>
