<HEADLINE> Canada Expected to Have 600,000 Millionaires in Five Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Canada has more than 300,000
millionaires today and the figure could double within five years,
the Ottawa Citizen reported Thursday,citing Toronto-based
professional services firm Ernst &AMP; Young.
</P>
<P>
This group of millionaires were folks with neither high incomes
nor super-successful businesses.
</P>
<P>
"These were just people who had accumulated financial assets
over 30 or 40 years on fairly modest incomes," Sherry Cooper, a
chief economist with the firm, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"You can't accumulate wealth unless you save money. The rate
of return on your investment is secondary to your ability to
accumulate capital," she said, adding "Studies have shown that the
self-made millionaires are generally those that are regularly
frugal."
</P>
<P>
Every few years, Ernst &AMP; Young publishes a report for its
financial institution clients on Canada's high-net-worth market,
using figures compiled from income-tax return information provided
by Revenue Canada.
</P>
<P>
At the end of 1996, the firm reported some 225,000 Canadians
with liquid assets totalling 1 million Canadian dollars or more.
</P>
