<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Durable-Goods Orders Fall in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Orders to U.S. factories
for big-ticket manufactured goods dropped in January, the first
decline since October, as the steep decline in orders for
electronic and other electrical equipment totally offset the
increase in orders for industrial machinery and primary metals,
the Commerce Department reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Total orders for durable goods, items expected to last at least
three years, dropped by 1.3 percent to a seasonally adjusted 214.8
billion U.S. dollars last month. That followed a revised 6.3
percent advance in December, the biggest gain in seven years.
</P>
<P>
Still, economists, who were predicting a decrease, have
cautioned that a drop in durable-goods orders shouldn't be viewed
as weakness in the industrial sector. Economists said the
underlying trend in orders remains firm and they expect
manufacturers to perform well this year.
</P>
<P>
Overall orders in January were 6.5 percent higher than the same
month last year.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Reserve has raised interest rates four times since
June, totaling a full percentage point. Even though those actions
made borrowing more expensive for businesses and consumers, the
higher rates still haven't had much impact in terms of
significantly slowing the economy. Given that, many economists
widely expect the central bank to raise rates again March 21.
</P>
<P>
Orders for electronic and other electrical equipment including
semiconductors, circuit boards, telecommunications equipment and
home appliances, fell by 13.2 percent last month, the largest
decrease since July 1997. In December, these orders rose by 5.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
And, transportation equipment orders fell by 3.6 percent in
January. Decreases in shipbuilding, tanks, airplanes and aircraft
parts more than offset increases in orders for cars and railroad
equipment. In December, transportation orders rose by a huge 23.2
percent.
</P>
<P>
Transportation often is volatile from month to month because it
includes such big purchases as airplanes. Excluding transportation,
overall orders fell last month by 0.5 percent, the first decline
since October.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, orders for industrial machinery, including computers
and machine tools, jumped by 12.3 percent last month, the
strongest pace since February 1985. Such orders fell by 2.5
percent in December. Orders for primary metals, the category that
includes steel, increased by 1.7 percent in January, following a 0.
5 percent decline the month before.
</P>
<P>
Shipments of big-ticket goods, a good signal of current demand,
grew by a solid 2.8 percent, marking the eighth increase in the
last nine months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
