<HEADLINE> U.S. Prison Blood Reported Unsafe for Use in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Health Canada blames U.S.
authorities for use of prison blood infected with both HIV and
hepatitis C, the Canadian Press reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The official response was written in a Health Department memo
obtained under Access-to-Information legislation, the report said.
</P>
<P>
"The use of these blood products in Canada can be attributed to
a failure by U.S. blood and regulatory authorities to inform a
Canadian blood broker that blood collected at prisons was no
longer safe and as a result was no longer being used in the U.S.,"
the memo was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 1,000 Canadian hemophiliacs were exposed to blood
products manufactured from plasma collected through U.S. prisons.
Many of the Canadian users have died, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Canadian hemophiliacs launched a lawsuit of 5
billion U.S. dollars against the U.S. Food and Drug Administration
for negligence despite evidence that prisons are rife with
infection-drug use and high-risk sex, the report said. 
</P>
