<DOCNO> XIE20000224.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Disappointed in WTO Ruling Against U.S. Trade Tax Breaks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The Clinton administration
on Thursday expressed its disappointments in the decision by the
Appellate Body of the World Trade Organization (WTO) which ruled
that a U.S. tax scheme affecting hundreds of billions of dollars
in industrial and agricultural exports violated global free trade
rules.
</P>
<P>
The three-member Appellate Body upheld a dispute panel ruling
of last October and agreed with the European Union that the
Foreign Sales Corporations (FSC) provisions of U.S. tax law
constituted a "prohibited exports subsidy."
</P>
<P>
The WTO panel recommended that the United States amend the
illegal system to bring it into line with WTO regulations
governing international trade.
</P>
<P>
"I am disappointed that the WTO Appellate Body has upheld the
panel's ruling," Treasury Secretary Lawrence H. Summers said. "The
FSC rules are widely viewed as creating a level playing field with
European tax systems and are important to our business community."
</P>
<P>
Summers said the U.S. government will work closely with the
Europeans, the business community and the Congress to achieve a
constructive solution.
</P>
<P>
"We strongly disagree with the appellate body's ruling," U.S.
Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky said. "Our view remains
that the FSC is completely consistent with U.S.-WTO obligations."
</P>
<P>
The FSC program enables U.S. makers of computer software,
chemicals, machinery and many other products to shield some export
income from taxes. The tax breaks for companies such as Microsoft,
Boeing and General Motors would be worth more than 15 billion U.S.
dollars over the next five years, according to congressional
estimates.
</P>
<P>
The European Union puts the five-year price tag at 17.5 billion
dollars; the Clinton administration estimates 7 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The program was created in 1984 to offset tax rebates European
companies get when they sell products outside the EU. It permits U.
S. companies to avoid certain income taxes by setting up export
subsidiaries on offshore tax havens such as the U.S. Virgin
Islands, Barbados and Guam.
</P>
<P>
The Europeans, on the other hand, contend the program has
reached beyond its original limits, particularly in 1997 when it
was extended to U.S. computer software-makers such as Microsoft.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000224.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
