<DOCNO> XIE20000224.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Okays U.N. Force for DRC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security
Council on Thursday morning voted unanimously to authorize the
deployment of 5,537 U.N. peace-keepers for the Democratic Republic
of Congo, including up to 500 military observers, to monitor the
shaky peace process in the Central African country.
</P>
<P>
After weeks of negotiations, the 15-nation body decided to
authorize "phased deployment" of the U.N. peace-keepers "in
conditions of adequate security and with the cooperation of the
parties."
</P>
<P>
The resolution approved the expansion of the U.N. Mission in
DRC, known as MONUC, and extend the its mandate until August 31.
</P>
<P>
Under the six-page resolution, the U.N. force is expected to
monitor the implementation of the Cease-fire Agreement and
investigate violations of the cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
Warring parties to the DRC conflict signed the Lusaka
Agreement on July 10 last year in Lusaka, capital of Zambia, but
repeated violations have been reported in the many-sided conflict.
</P>
<P>
The expanded U.N. Mission is expected to establish and
maintain continuous liaison with the field headquarters of all the
parties' military forces and to work with the parties to obtain
the release of all prisoners of war, military captives and remains
in cooperation with international humanitarian agencies.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. peace-keepers are also mandated to supervise and
verify the disengagement and redeployment of the parties' forces,
the resolution said.
</P>
<P>
The resolution also spelt out the conditions for the U.N.
military deployment. They include: the parties respect and uphold
the Cease-fire Agreement and the relevant Council resolutions, a
valid plan for the disengagement of the parties' forces and the
parties provide "firm and credible assurances," prior to the U.N.
deployment, for the security and freedom of movement of U.N. and
related personnel.
</P>
<P>
The resolution, which said that the current DRC conflict "
constitutes a threat to international peace and security in the
region," reaffirmed the sovereignty, territorial integrity and
political independence of DRC and all States in the region, and
also the sovereignty of DRC over its natural resources.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council, in the resolution, voiced the strong
support for the Lusaka Cease-fire Agreement, saying it "represents
the most viable basis for the peaceful resolution of the conflict"
in the African country.
</P>
<P>
The resolution reiterated its calls for "the orderly
withdrawal of all foreign forces from the territory of the
Democratic Republic of the Congo in accordance with the Cease-fire
Agreement."
</P>
<P>
Before the vote, Wang Yingfan, Chinese permanent
representative to the United Nations, told the Security Council
that "It is our long-held position that respect for the
sovereignty and territorial integrity of DRC and the effective
implementation of the Lusaka Cease-fire Agreement form the basis
for the resolution of the question in DRC."
</P>
<P>
What will be authorized by the Security Council is intended
only to assist the implement of part of the Lusaka Agreement, so "
more and harder tasks are before the international community and
parties to the conflict, and call for their concerted efforts,"
Wang said.
</P>
<P>
The DRC conflict broke out in August 1998 when rebels, backed
by Uganda and Rwanda, launched an offensive to oust President
Laurent Kabila's government. It has soaked up fighting forces from
at least six African countries -- with troops from Zimbabwe,
Namibia and Angola all fighting on Kabila's side. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000224.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
