<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian President Appeals For End of Intolerance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Italian President Carlo Azeglio
Ciampi Thursday renewed his appeal for an end to all forms of
intolerance, in a speech delivered during a visit to a number of
tragic World War Two sites in Italian northeast city of Trieste
which remain symbols of violence and persecution.
</P>
<P>
"Every feeling of bitterness and hatred must come to an end.
Together, we must honor our dead and think of the future of our
people. The future lies in European peace," Ciampi said.
</P>
<P>
His words came during a visit to the "foiba" of Basovizza, a
mountain chasm in Istria where, between 1943 and 1945, thousands
of Italians and opponents of the Communist regime in Yugoslavia
were hurled to their deaths by Yugoslav forces.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Thursday, Ciampi visited the San Sabba rice farm in
Trieste, the site of Italy's only Nazi death camp and where some 5,
000 Jewish people perished.
</P>
<P>
Ciampi's visit to the city and its massacre sites is of special
significance since the region of Friuli-Venezia Giulia, of which
Trieste is the capital, is just across the border from the
Austrian province of Carinthia, of which far-right leader Joerg
Haider is governor.
</P>
<P>
Haider's declaration that he also intends to visit the death
camp has sparked bitter controversy here, as has the centre-right
regional government's voting of a resolution supporting the
Austrian leader in the aftermath of his xenophobic Freedom Party's
rise to power in Austria.
</P>
<P>
On February 16, the Lower House voted a resolution against the
Haider visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
