<HEADLINE> Mozambique to Revise Budget due to Floods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican Prime Minister
Pascoal Mocumbi on Thursday said that the catastrophic flooding in
southern and central Mozambique has forced the government to
revise this year's plan and budget.
</P>
<P>
"We have to divert resources that were originally planned to
allocate to other areas", Mocumbi said. "The government's plans
for this year will be affected".
</P>
<P>
In particular, money earmarked for secondary and tertiary
roads might now have to be spent on repairing the trunk road
network, and particularly the main north-south highway, washed
away by the floods in several places.
</P>
<P>
The flood has not affected this year's harvest, Mocumbi said.
The most fertile parts of the country are in the northern
provinces, they have not suffered from flooding and are expected
to produce a good harvest.
</P>
<P>
In the south "we can still recover" only if there was immediate
 replanting once the flood waters subsided, he said.
</P>
<P>
The government's top priorities, he said, remained humanitarian
 assistance for the flood victims, and reopening access roads into
the affected areas, so that relief goods could be taken in by road
rather than by helicopter.
</P>
<P>
"All humanitarian assistance to Gaza and to part of Maputo
Province is now being undertaken by air," he said. "That's very
expensive and not very efficient."
</P>
<P>
"The quicker we can reopen the roads, thets appeal on Wednesday for 65.5 million dollars in
emergency aid, "but I think this is an underestimate", said
Mocumbi. 
</P>
