<HEADLINE> Announcement of Election Results in Tehran Delayed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The parliamentary election
results in Iran's capital of Tehran will come out 24 hours later
than scheduled, Director General of the Election Headquarters at
the Interior Ministry Javad Qadimi Zaker said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
All votes from Tehran have been counted, but the ministry's
executive board and the Supervisory Board decided to re-count 105
ballot boxes to make sure that there has been no rigging, Zaker was
quoted by the Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA) as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said the executive board took 50 boxes and the Supervisory
Board took another 55 ballot boxes to re-count the votes. There are
altogether 36,000 ballot boxes in Tehran.
</P>
<P>
He predicted the final results will be released by late Thursday
night or Friday.
</P>
<P>
IRNA said on Wednesday the final results for Tehran will be
announced mid-Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The latest results of last Friday's parliamentary election
showed that 191 seats out of a total of 290 have been confirmed,
with reformists winning 137, the conservatives taking only 39, and
the rest going to independents.
</P>
<P>
Some 69 seats have to be decided in run-off elections to be held
in April because the candidates involved failed to get the minimum
25 percent of the total votes to land a seat in the 290-member
sixth Majlis (parliament).
</P>
<P>
Now the attention is focused on Tehran, where the latest results
showed that reformists of the May 23 Front may finally get 29 of
the constituency's share of 30 seats in the new parliament.
</P>
<P>
Conservative newspapers predicted on Thursday the former
President Hashemi Rafsanjani will be able to enter the list of 30
parliament members in Tehran, while other papers suggest he may
lose in the end.
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani, one of the most senior politicians in Iran, has
posed himself as a centrist but was reportedly close to the
conservatives.
</P>
<P>
With reformists winning a sweeping victory in the election, the
conservatives have pinned their hope on Rafsanjani to enter the
parliament and become the new speaker. 
</P>
</TEXT>
