<HEADLINE> Mayon Evacuees Count Exceeds 18,000 Mark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The number of people housed in
evacuation centers, due to Thursday's Mayon eruption, throughout
Albay Province in the southeastern Philippines has reached 18,018,
the government said.
</P>
<P>
According to the records issued by the Department of Social
Welfare and Development, the evacuees, or about 3,226 families,
are from Albay's seven towns and are mostly housed in Legazpi city.
</P>
<P>
There were all in all 24 affected villages from where the
evacuees came from.
</P>
<P>
The Albay provincial board has reportedly officially declared
the province in a state of calamity, to pave the way for the usage
of the calamity fund.
</P>
<P>
The provincial board, headed by Albay Vice Governor Jesus
Calisin,unanimously approved the proposal and the calamity funds
which amount to about 3 million pesos (75,000 U.S. dollars) will
be used to purchase foodstuffs for the evacuees.
</P>
<P>
But reports said the approval of the budget for Legazpi city is
still under review, adding that Legazpi, 10 kilometers away from
Mt.Mayon, still needs the concurrence of the Albay provincial
board for its budget.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Philippine Air Transportation Office (ATO)
announced also the cancellation of all commercial flights to
Legazpi in view of the worsening volcanic activity there.
</P>
<P>
"We have closed Legazpi Airport until further notice to avert
any air incidents which could occur while hazardous levels of
eruption in Mount Mayon is in progress and because of ash-falls,"
ATO Executive Director Roland Luna said.
</P>
<P>
Mayon Volcano erupted Thursday morning, sending lava fountains
and huge columns of smoke to the sky as local residents fled their
homes to evacuation centers.
</P>
<P>
The 2,462-meter Mayon Volcano has erupted at least 40 times
since 1616 and its last major eruption was in 1993, which killed
some 70 persons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
