<HEADLINE> Simitis: Kosovo Must Remain Part of Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Greek Prime Minister Costas
Simitis Thursday reiterated Athens' position that Kosovo must
retain its status as an autonomous province inside the borders of
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after talks with visiting NATO Secretary General
George Robertson, Simitis expressed concern over the increasingly
worsening situation in Kosovo, saying that the developments are
leading to tensions which must be put under control.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed that NATO's presence in Kosovo should ensure
equilibrium in the multiethnic society of Kosovo, which has seen
rising violence between NATO-led peacekeepers, ethnic Albanians
and Serbs.
</P>
<P>
The local press Thursday criticized the NATO-led peacekeepers
for their failure in preserving Kosovo's bicommunal status, and
regarded this as a source of crises that are becoming increasingly
hard to control in the region.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Robertson, who arrived here Wednesday on a two-day
visit as part of a courtesy tour of alliance member states, said
that the situation in the violence-torn Kosovo town of Mitrovica
was better than in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, two French soldiers were wounded and one ethnic
Albanian sniper died in a gunfight in the northern Kosovo town.
</P>
<P>
Robertson said that a NATO meeting would discuss Friday a
proposal for the movement of troops in the area. However, he did
not consider it necessary for the reinforcement of the NATO-led
peacekeepers at this time.
</P>
<P>
Robertson, who is on his first visit to Greece, had also
discussed with Simitis EU-NATO relations in the framework of
building a European security and defense identity and the
relations between Greece and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
He praised Athens' important and leadership role in maintaining
peace in the Balkan region and welcomed the recent rapprochement
between the two neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
Later in the day, the NATO chief will also have talks with
Greek Foreign Minister George Papandreou and Defense Minister Akis
Tsohatzopoulos. 
</P>
</TEXT>
