<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Inflation Down in January: Statistics  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Canada's annual inflation fell
to 2.3 percent in January from December's 2.6 percent, with
consumer prices declining 0.1 percent, Statistics Canada reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The reported figures are running counter to inflation fear
fueled by rising energy charges. Gasoline, in particular, was
already priced at a record high of 69.7 cents (about 0.48 U.S.
dollars) a liter Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The official inflation figures are also much lower than the
expected monthly rise of 0.4 percent and annual rate of 2.8
percent.
</P>
<P>
Core inflation, excluding volatile food and energy prices, fell
to 1.4 percent from 1.6 percent in December, as compared with the
1.8 percent forecast by analysts.
</P>
<P>
Monthly rise for energy prices was reported to be 0.2 percent
in January, with the annual rate being put at 15 percent. The
monthly rise was led by a 2.4 percent hike in natural gas price
and a 2.1 percent increase in fuel oil. 
</P>
</TEXT>
