<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Wins WTO Case Against U.S. Export Subsidy Scheme </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission said
Thursday the World Trade Organization (WTO) had ruled that U.S.
subsidies to exports through the Foreign Sales Corporation (FSC)
scheme breach the WTO rules.
</P>
<P>
The ruling upholds an essential conclusion from a WTO dispute
settlement panel that the U.S. needs to bring FSC into conformity
with its WTO obligations by the beginning of the next U.S. fiscal
year, the EU's executive body said.
</P>
<P>
The panel's report issued last October said the U.S. would have
to withdraw the FSC scheme because it was designed as a tax haven
for American corporations to exempt substantial amount of due
taxes.
</P>
<P>
"We welcome this decision," said EU Trade Commissioner Pascal
Lamy, "The FSC system, and its predecessor, have had a major
negative effect on international trade to the detriment of
European companies.... It is now for the U.S. to implement the
WTO's findings, in line with its international obligations."
</P>
<P>
The EU sued the U.S. over the FSC scheme under the WTO Dispute
Settlement Understanding in 1997. The two sides had held several
rounds of consultations but failed to reach any agreement.
</P>
<P>
After the panel issued its report in favor of the EU, the U.S.
filed a Notice of Appeal to the WTO dispute settlement body on
November 26.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics, FSC subsidies have assisted U.S.
exports worth 250 billion dollars, giving U.S. companies an unfair
advantage and creating major distortions of international trade.
The U.S. budgetary cost for the subsidies is around 3.5 million
dollars per year, said the EU. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
