<HEADLINE> Bus Fumes Kill Two Passengers in East China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QINGDAO, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Investigations have shown that
the cause for the February 21 killing of two passengers in east
China's Shandong Province was toxic fumes emitted by the bus they
were riding in.
</P>
<P>
Hu Yingyi, assistant to the director of Qingdao Municipal
Health Bureau, told Xinhua today that a team of investigators
found that carbon monoxide emitted from the long-distance bus
also poisoned 35 women farmers who were traveling from their
hometown of Heze to another town for jobs.
</P>
<P>
Investigators found that tailpipe exhaust leaked into the bus
through cracks under the seats of the two dead women, killing them
and poisoning the 35 others.
</P>
<P>
At present, five women are still in critical condition and
receiving emergency treatment in a nearby hospital, Hu said.
</P>
<P>
The possibility of food poisoning or intentional poisoning has
been ruled out, she added.
</P>
<P>
Further investigations into responsibility for the accident is
still underway. 
</P>
</TEXT>
