<HEADLINE> HK SFC Criticizes Sponsor for Poor Arrangement in IPO of Tom.com </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Securities and
Futures Commission (SFC) Thursday criticized the concerning
parties in the initial public offering (IPO) of the Internet
company tom.com for failing to take necessary measures to prevent
chaos.
</P>
<P>
"SFC is disappointed that the sponsor, receiving bank and
company concerned, despite our advice through the Stock Exchange
of Hong Kong, have not prepared sufficient subscription forms in a
timely manner and set up proper arrangements for receiving the
forms," said a SFC announcement.
</P>
<P>
"The company, sponsor and receiving bank should have been aware
of the investor interest in the IPO, particularly in view of the
publicity running up to the IPO," it said.
</P>
<P>
The SFC has asked BNP Prime Peregrine, the sponsor, lead
manager and global coordinator of the IPO, to submit a report on
the case.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday morning, an estimated 300,000 Hong Kong people
lined up outside 10 HSBC (Hong Kong and Shanghai Banking
Corporation Limited) branches to submit application forms for
shares in tom.com, which is 57 percent owned by Hutchison Whampoa
and Cheung Kong (Holdings) Ltd., both controlled by Hong Kong
tycoon Li Ka-shing.
</P>
<P>
The order at several bank branches was so chaotic that extra
policemen had to be deployed.
</P>
<P>
The SFC also said the development of a financial infrastructure
for electronic subscription at IPOs will be speeded up to obviate
the need to queue up for forms and to hand in the forms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
