<HEADLINE> Diplomatic News Highlights (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China today voiced its strong dissatisfaction with and resolute
opposition to the United States stance on the Taiwan issue,
stating that it has infringed upon China's sovereignty and grossly
interferred in China's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan is an inalienable part of China and the Taiwan issue is
absolutely China's internal affairs that no foreign country should
interfere in, said Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao at a
press conference when asked to comment on the U.S. State
Department's "deep concern" on "China's threat" to Taiwan
contained in a white paper issued by China on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Also, the spokesman expressed China's concern over reports
that the Japanese government will allow the Dalai Lama to go to
Japan for a visit.
</P>
<P>
"The Dalai Lama is a political exile under the disguise of
religion, who has been engaged in long-term separatist activities,
" he said, urging the Japanese government to honor its commitments
of not letting the Dalai Lama enter the Japanese territory so as
to avoid new disturbances in bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
With regard to the successor of Michel Camdessus, former
managing director of the International Monetary Fund (IMF), Zhu
said China hopes that the IMF will choose its new leader as soon
as possible.
</P>
<P>
He also said that Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan's recent visit
to Mauritania, Tunis, Kuwait and Iran has been crowned with a
complete success.
</P>
<P>
Zhu announced at the conference that Russian Deputy Prime
Minister Ilya Klebanov will pay an official visit to China from
March 2 to 4, and Thai Deputy Prime Minister Bhichai Rattakul will
visit China from February 27 to March 2.
</P>
<P>
Vietnamese Foreign Minister Arrives in Beijing
</P>
<P>
Vietnamese Foreign Minister Nguyen Dy Nien arrived here this
evening for a four-day official visit to China, at the invitation
of his Chinese counterpart Tang Jiaxuan.
</P>
<P>
This is Nien's first China visit since he took the post last
month.
</P>
<P>
During his stay, Nien is expected to meet Chinese leaders and
confer with Tang on bilateral relations and other issues of common
concern. 
</P>
