<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gold Prices Nose-dive in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Prices of gold nose-dived on
the bullion market Thursday in Mumbai (Bombay) due to a steep fall
of international prices and silver also closed weak.
</P>
<P>
Standard gold opened sharply weak at 4,750 rupees (110.47 U.S.
dollar) per 10 grams and fell further to end at 4,740 rupees (110.
23 dollars), showing a notable fall of 70 rupees (1.63 dollars)
over the last close of 4,810 rupees (111.86 dollars).
</P>
<P>
Twenty-two-carat gold was quoted sharply lower at 4,385 rupees
(101.98 dollars) per 10 grams as against the last level of 4,450
rupees (103.49 dollars).
</P>
<P>
Ready silver (.999 fineness) closed at 8,205 rupees (190.81
dollars) per kilogram, showing a fall of 25 rupees (0.58 dollars)
over the last close of 8,230 rupees (191.4 dollars).
</P>
<P>
Raw silver (.916 fineness) declined to 8,080 rupees (187.9
dollars) per kilogram from 8,110 rupees (188.6 dollars) previously.
</P>
</TEXT>
