<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB to Open Resident Mission in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank
announced Thursday that it will establish one of its largest
resident missions in Beijing, China's capital city, to boost
economic cooperation with China.
</P>
<P>
The Manila-based financial agency said in a statement issued
here that the mission, which is expected to open by mid-2000, will
have an initial staff of 17 officers, including 11 Chinese
nationals, and up to 20 administrative staff.
</P>
<P>
The mission will "enable us to provide a better service to one
of our most important clients, the People's Republic of China,"
the statement quoted ADB President Tadao Chino as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing office will also improve the ADB's ability to
promote regional coordination, particularly for the greater Mekong
subregion and the Central Asian republics, said Bruce Murry, ADB's
program manager for China.
</P>
<P>
The ADB's operations in China have grown in size and complexity
since the country joined the ADB in 1986, the statement said,
adding that the ADB has approved for China loans totaling 9.6
billion U.S. dollars and technical assistance grants amounting to
166 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
