<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's NITC Discusses New Economic Framework </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's National
Information Technology Council (NITC) Thursday discussed the new
economic framework, in which knowledge is increasingly recognized
as a vital source of economic growth, determinant of wealth and
basis of competitive advantage.
</P>
<P>
At its 9th meeting chaired by Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad,
the council deliberated on issues and challenges pertaining to the
shift in the k-economy, in particular on how to harness the
embedded knowledge to enhance the value chain and help achieve
Malaysia's vision of becoming an information-rich and value-based
society by 2020, NITC said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also positioned the Multimedia Super Corridor and
the National IT Agenda as excellent start-ups to drive and develop
a good framework to guide Malaysia's transition to the knowledge
economy, NITC said.
</P>
<P>
It said Malaysia had a window of opportunity to position itself
since the k-economy was only just emerging and its transition
might not be smooth sailing.
</P>
<P>
The meeting Thursday elaborated on a new strategy to enable the
Malaysian economy to move closer to its goals of harnessing
knowledge as a commodity to be exchanged and to be used to create
new value,it said.
</P>
<P>
As knowledge-based products and services have become the
dominant force of commerce, knowledge itself would also emerge as
the new currency in the Malaysian economy, it said.
</P>
<P>
The NITC announced the setting up of a k-economy work research
group entrusted with the task of identifying and developing k-
economy measures to monitor and gauge Malaysia's progress in this
area, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
