<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan, Zambian Presidents Hold Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni held talks with his Zambian counterpart Frederick Chiluba
on bilateral relations and issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
A press release from the President's Office said Thursday that
President Chiluba Wednesday called on Museveni in Lusaka's Pamodzi
Hotel where Museveni was attending a one-day summit on the
conflict in the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
The meeting had reportedly drawn nine regional leaders, most of
whose countries are militarily involved in the 18-month-long DRC
civil war.
</P>
<P>
Uganda's involvement in the conflict and the implementation of
the nearly faltering Lusaka cease-fire agreement were high on
their agenda.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Museveni discussed with Namibian leader Sam Nujoma on
bilateral relations, the press release said.
</P>
<P>
Museveni, accompanied by State Minister for Regional Affairs
Amama Mbabazi, left for Lusaka Wednesday morning. The summit, a
follow-up to the U.N. meeting on the same topic last month,
called for more international financial and logistic support for
the implementation of the Lusaka pact. All warring parties to the
conflict reaffirmed their commitment to the agreement they penned
last July and August. 
</P>
</TEXT>
