<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Washington Post
</P>
<P>
-- Burning money faster than planned, second-guessing some key
decisions and reeling from its loss in Michigan Tuesday, Texas
Governor George W. Bush's campaign struggled Wednesday to maintain
the perception that Bush was the front-runner and the candidate
best positioned to claim the Republican nomination.
</P>
<P>
-- Amid surge of rioting and ethnic violence in northern Kosovo,
Army General Wesley K. Clark, NATO's top European commander,
urgently appealed Wednesday for more allied troops to be sent to
the troubled Serbian province.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times
</P>
<P>
-- Many staunch supporters of Governor George W. Bush said they
were shocked by Senator John McCain's primary victories in
Michigan and Arizona on Tuesday. Bush sought to regroup by
agreeing to debate in Los Angeles next week and altering his
schedule, but he expressed confidence that his strength among
Republican voters would gain him the nomination.
</P>
<P>
-- Fears that the United States, Britain and other English-
speaking countries are using a cold-war eavesdropping network to
gain a commercial edge roused passions across Europe, even after
the notion was denied in Washington and London.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal
</P>
<P>
-- The Nasdaq index climbed 168.21 points to a record 4550.33,
despite Greenspan's warning that the stock market and economy are
too strong. The Dow Jones industrials fell 79.11.
</P>
<P>
-- A prestigious medical journal conceded in an unusual
apology to readers that it had violated its own disclosure
guidelines by publishing drug evaluations by doctors who received
funding from manufacturers. The New England Journal of Medicine
found 19 instances since 1997. 
</P>
