<HEADLINE> Iran's Foreign Ministry Summons Turkish Ambassador </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Deputy Foreign Minister
for Asia and the Pacific Mohsen Aminzadeh on Thursday summoned
Turkish ambassador to Iran, Turan Murali, to protest a statement
made by Turkish Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit was quoted by the media as saying in the wake of Iran's
sixth parliamentary elections that Iran will no longer support
Islamic movements in other countries.
</P>
<P>
The final results of the elections, held last Friday, have not
come out yet, but it is already known that reformists will get an
absolute majority in the 290-seat legislative body, which could
help push through President Mohammed Khatami's reform policies.
</P>
<P>
Aminzadeh said the statement made by the Turkish prime minister
is a clear example of interference in Iran's domestic affairs and
an affront to the Iranian people and the Islamic Republic.
</P>
<P>
"Ecevit's statement not only runs counter to the good neighborly
relations between Iran and Turkey, but also conveys lack of
understanding of the historical and political development in Iran
on the part of Mr. Ecevit," Aminzadeh said, quoted by the Islamic
Republic News Agency.
</P>
<P>
He said the Islamic revolution became victorious in 1979 by the
Iranian people and the same people have now made a large turnout
for the parliamentary elections to safeguard the achievements of
the revolution.
</P>
<P>
"We are confident that the Muslim people of Turkey have not the
same view that the prime minister expressed about Iran," Aminzadeh
said.
</P>
<P>
"We hope the Turkish officials will accurately understand the
situation, correct their wrong conducts and avoid bringing more
misunderstanding between the two nations," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish ambassador said he would convey Iran's protest to
the Turkish officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
