<HEADLINE> Talks with Mubarak on Mideast Peace "Excellent": U. S. Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 24 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Mideast peace envoy Dennis
Ross termed as "excellent" his talks with Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak here on Thursday on the developments of the Middle East
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Ross, who arrived here earlier in the day after visiting Israel
and the Palestinian self-rule areas, said he briefed Mubarak on his

talks with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
The peace process is facing certain difficulties but the two
sides have shown desire to move forward with the peace talks, said
the U.S. envoy.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, said Ross, he discussed with Mubarak how Egypt
and the U.S. can work together to break the deadlock in the
Israeli-Palestinian talks which ground to a halt two weeks ago due
to a dispute over a long-delayed Israeli troop withdrawal from the
West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Asked to comment on a statement by U.S. State Department
spokesman
James Rubin that President Mubarak's visit to Lebanon on Saturday
was meant to show support to the Iranian-backed Hezbollah guerrilla
group, Ross said that Egypt and the U.S. were partners in search of
peace and that the Mideast peace process depended on such a
partnership.
</P>
<P>
The partnership focuses on advancing the peace process as a
whole, said Ross.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, the first Arab country to sign a peace treaty with Israel
in 1979, became the second biggest recipient of U.S. foreign aid
after Israel. It receives about 2 billion U.S. dollars a year, much
of which are in military supplies.
</P>
<P>
Ross also met with Foreign Minister Amr Moussa in the day.
</P>
</TEXT>
