<HEADLINE> Egyptian Engineers Go to Lebanon to Repair Damaged Power Stations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The first batch of Egyptian
engineers left here Thursday for Lebanon to repair the three power
stations badly damaged by the recent Israeli airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Minister of Electricity and Energy Ali el-Saeedi said
the technical team led by engineer Galal Abdel Hlawa will begin
their work as soon as they arrive despite the required devices are
shipped as of Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The preliminary costs of the whole project are estimated at 80
million Egyptian pounds (about 24 million U.S. dollars), el-Saeedi
said.
</P>
<P>
Illustrating a detailed timetable for recovering the three
stations, the minister said that new high-tech devices will be
installed at the 40-percent-damaged Beir Nabouh station in seven
weeks.
</P>
<P>
It will take 60 days to repair the 60-percent-damaged Gomhour
station, he said, adding that the last station in Baalbek was
totally destroyed, so it will take much more time because large
transformers are needed.
</P>
<P>
Claiming to revenge the killing of Israeli soldiers by the
Hezbollah guerrillas in south Lebanon, the Israeli air force staged
a massive air raids on civilian targets in Lebanon on February 8,
seriously damaging the three power stations.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a security zone in south Lebanon in 1985 with an
alleged aim of protecting its northern territories from cross-
border guerrilla attacks.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah, an Iranian- and Syrian-backed military group, has
been spearheading a war of attrition to oust the Israeli occupation
troops and the Israeli-allied South Lebanon Army. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
