<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Still Committed to Dialogue With India: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan has continued to
pursue a policy of dialogue and peaceful resolution of the core
dispute of Kashmir and other issues with India since the inception
of the new government.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the concluding session of a seminar on foreign
policy here on Thursday, Pakistan's Foreign Office spokesman Tariq
Altaf said Pakistan-India relations are currently,perhaps, at
their lowest ebb in the last three decades.
</P>
<P>
New Delhi is engaged in its blind pursuit of a "hate Pakistan
campaign," he charged, adding that since October 12 India has
practically ceased any dealings with Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that Pakistan, however, remains prepared to
fulfill all its obligations and implement the agreements it has
entered into.
</P>
<P>
"The Lahore process, as it came to be known, was essentially an
endorsement of the ongoing dialogue process. The dialogue has been
stonewalled by India."
</P>
<P>
Former Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif, who was dismissed
in a bloodless coup in October last year, met his Indian
counterpart, Atal Behari Vajpayee, in Lahore a year ago and both
promised to make efforts to solve all outstanding issues between
the two rivals through dialogue.
</P>
<P>
Altaf said Chief Executive General Pervez Musharraf has
repeatedly offered to engage in a result-oriented dialogue with
India focusing on Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
In an interview a fortnight ago, General Musharraf made a
direct offer to meet Vajpayee.
</P>
<P>
According to Altaf, the chief executive stressed that the two
sides could break the logjam and reduce tensions by addressing the
Kashmir issue.
</P>
<P>
On the contrary, he said, Vajpayee shrugged off any possibility
of dialogue with Pakistan unless the latter gives up its control
over its part of Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
"The contrast in the approaches of the two countries to vital
issues of peace and security cannot but be noticed by the
international community," Altaf said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
