<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brunei Government Sues Sultan's Brother Over Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The Brunei government and
its investment arm, Brunei Investment Agency (BIA), have started
legal action against and frozen the assets of the sultanate's
former Finance Minister Prince Jefri Bolkiah for improper
withdrawal and use of substantial state reserve fund.
</P>
<P>
Besides Prince Jefri, a younger brother of Sultan Hassanal
Bolkiah, civil proceedings had also commenced against Prince Jefri
's son, Prince Abdul Hakeem, and his former Private and
Confidential Secretary Haji Awang bin Kassim, Malaysia's national
news agency Bernama reported, quoting a Brunei government
statement from Brunei's capital Bandar Seri Begawan Thursday
evening.
</P>
<P>
Similar action was also being taken against more than 60
companies overseas believed to be owned or controlled by Prince
Jefri, who resigned as finance minister in 1998 after the Amedeo
group of companies that he controlled reported losses of tens of
billions of Brunei dollars.
</P>
<P>
Other individuals or companies might be drawn into the
proceedings later on, which "were undertaken after efforts to find
solution through other means had failed and had not produced any
satisfactory results," according to the statement signed by
Permanent Secretary to the Office of the Prime Minister Hazair
Abdullah faxed to the news agency, Bernama said.
</P>
<P>
The proceedings were started following detailed investigations
into the affairs of the BIA carried out by a financial task force
since its appointment in June 1998 headed by Education Minister
and Acting Health Minister Abdul Aziz Umar.
</P>
<P>
"The claims brought against His Royal Highness (Prince Jefri)
relate to the improper withdrawal and use of substantial funds
from the BIA, which constitutes the state reserve fund, during the
period when His Royal Highness was minister of finance and
chairman of BIA,"the statement said.
</P>
<P>
It said orders had also been obtained from the Brunei High
Court freezing Prince Jefri's assets both in Brunei and overseas
and those of a number of other defendants.
</P>
<P>
These included a substantial number of residential properties
overseas.
</P>
<P>
It said a related order had also been obtained in the English
High Court freezing Prince Jefri's assets in Britain.
</P>
<P>
"Proceedings seeking similar orders in other countries may also
be necessary," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Amedeo, a huge development consortium, collapsed in July 1998
amid reports of huge losses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
