<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Denies Reported Secret Talks with Syria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister Ehud Barak's
office Thursday denied local media reports that Israel and Syria
were conducting secret talks, saying they were not true.
</P>
<P>
The local daily Maariv reported Thursday that Israel and Syria
were engaging in accelerated secret talks through U.S. mediation,
and Barak had held marathon talks with his negotiating team.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Syrian talks, which resumed last December after a
nearly four-year freeze, broke off in January over a dispute on the
fate of the Golan Heights, a Syrian plateau seized by Israel in the
1967 Middle East War.
</P>
<P>
Syria accused Israel of refusing to focus on the return of the
Golan Heights in the first two rounds of talks, insisting that
Israel make a written commitment to a full withdrawal from the
heights before the talks could be reopened. Israel has rejected the
demand.
</P>
<P>
Despite the stalemate, mediation efforts led by the U.S. have
been going on. U.S. President Bill Clinton is especially eager to
see a peace treaty being clinched in the Middle East before he
leaves office next January.
</P>
<P>
Barak also wants to reach a peace agreement with Damascus which
would help him fulfil a key election promise to pull Israeli troops
out of southern Lebanon by July. Syria is the main power broker in
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
There have been various reports in the last few days saying that
the talks would be resumed soon. Maariv reported one week ago that
Israel and Syria had agreed in principle to revive talks within two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
Holding secret talks is a common political game in the Middle
East since it can relieve internal or external pressures on both
sides. The most typical was the Israeli-Palestinian negotiation
over the historic Oslo accords seven years ago.
</P>
<P>
While their public negotiations in Washington led to nowhere,
the two sides surprised the whole world by announcing that they had
reached an agreement through secret negotiations in Oslo, Norway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000224.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- In the wake of a legislation allowing international
arbitration in power contracts, 28 contractors have applied to the
Turkish Energy Ministry to revise their earlier-sealed contracts,
Turkish Daily News reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Parliament passed a bill on January 21, allowing
international arbitration for existing and earlier-sealed
contracts.
</P>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- Syria and the Democratic People's Republic of Korea
signed here an agreement on the prevention of dual-taxation and tax
evasion between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed to boost cooperation and cement
economic and commercial ties between the two countries. Under the
deal, incomes of citizens residing in any of the two countries will
not be subject to tax obligations.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan and Israel agreed to activate the Jordanian-
Israeli Committee of Transport by forming specialized technical
commissions which will meet regularly.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Minister of Transport Issa Ayub said the committee is
expected to hold its first meeting next Sunday.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting held Thursday, the Israeli side presented a
proposal on the operation of the Alsalam airport in Aqaba.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- The number of factories in operation in Saudi Arabia
stood at 3,148, with a total capital of more than 232 billion rials
(61.9 billion U.S. dollars) and the number of workers also rose to
about 292,000, Saudi Press Agency quoted official statistics as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The factories specialized in the chemical industries and plastic
production ranked the first, followed by factories in producing
Chinese porcelain, building materials, textiles, ready-made
garments and industries in manufacturing metal products, equipment
and food stuff.
</P>
<P>
The value of Saudi industrial exports to foreign countries is
estimated at 15 billion rials (4 billion dollars) per year.
</P>
</TEXT>
