<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Defends Levy's Harsh Comments on Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak Thursday defended Foreign Minister David Levy's controversial
comments on Lebanon, in which Levy threatened to launch "child-for-
child" revenge for possible guerrilla attacks.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint press conference with visiting French Prime
Minister Lionel Jospin, Barak denied that he had tried to confine
his foreign minister's speech.
</P>
<P>
What Levy had said, according to Barak, stressed just how great
the Israeli government views it responsibility for maintaining
national security, which had been threatened recently by "a wave of
hatred" across the Arab world.
</P>
<P>
Levy declared in Wednesday's Knesset (Parliament) session that
if Lebanese Hezbollah guerrillas attacked Jewish settlements along
Israel's northern border, Lebanon would pay "blood for blood, soul
for soul, child for child."
</P>
<P>
Levy was commenting on Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak's recent
statements in support of Hezbollah and "incitement" from the Arab
countries against Israel.
</P>
<P>
He said he had possessed information that Hezbollah had Katyusha
rockets ready to launch at the Upper Galilee area in northern
Israel. Thus, he said, he wanted his comments could be clear, "not
as a threat, but as a warning before a calamity."
</P>
<P>
Levy's commensurate revenge policy immediately sparked ruckus in
the Knesset and his speech was interrupted several times by angry
shout-out from some dovish Knesset members.
</P>
<P>
Zahava Galon, Meretz faction head in the Knesset, called on
Barak to put Levy in his place. She said that someone whose idea of
diplomacy and security is "an eye for an eye, a tooth for a tooth"
is not fit to serve in the inner-circle security cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Issam Mahoul, from the Hadash party, said: "Child for child is a
primitive, fundamentalist and dangerous expression...that not
suited to governments."
</P>
<P>
Levy's comments followed by his controversial remarks earlier in
the month that "if Israeli northern settlements burn, Lebanese soil
will burn."
</P>
<P>
These comments show that Israel faces the dilemma of violating
moral rules and bombing villages and even hurting innocent villages
or trying to endure Hezbollah's recent escalation activities in the
Israeli-occupied security zone in South Lebanon, which had killed
seven Israeli soldiers and wounded a dozen since the beginning of
this year.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a buffer zone in South Lebanon in 1985 with a
self-declared purpose of protecting its northern border areas from
cross-border guerrilla attacks.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese Shiite Muslim militant group Hezbollah, or Party of
God, has been fighting to end Israeli occupation there.
</P>
<P>
To avenge Hezbollah's deadly attacks in the past few weeks,
Israeli troops struck at three Lebanese power stations supplying
electricity to Beirut and other Lebanese cities, wounding at least
a dozen civilians and leading to a total damage of 200 million U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Israel Defense Forces (IDF) Chief of Staff Shaul Mofaz
submitted a policy-changing plan to Israeli security cabinet,
asking for approval to fire back Hezbollah guerrillas hidden in
villages, which will surely cause great civilian casualties.
</P>
<P>
These decisions invited severe criticisms from Arab countries
and even the United States, the major patron of Israel in the world
political arena. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000224.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CITES Asian Regional Meeting Ends in Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, February 24 (Xinhua) -- A four-day Asian Regional
Meeting of the Convention on International Trade in Endangered
Species(CITES) came to an end here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Some 100 representatives of CITES members and non-members and
observers from 45 countries attended the four-day meeting hosted
by Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
The main purpose of this meeting was to study and exchange
experiences among the CITES member countries in Asia for
discussion at the 11th CITES Conference of the Parties (COP),
which is scheduled to be held in Nairobi, Kenya in April 2000.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, representatives from China strongly urged the
consumer states to list the Tibetan antelope as a priority species,
implement strict law enforcement measures and severely punish
relevant selling and smuggling activities.
</P>
<P>
"This CITES Asian Regional Meeting has been a firm step toward
improving the effectiveness and efficiency of CITES implementation
in all countries in this region," Cambodian Minister of
Agriculture,Forestry and Fishery Chhea Song said at the closing
meeting.
</P>
<P>
CITES at present has 145 members, and Cambodia became a member
in October 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
