<HEADLINE> Nigerian State Extends Restriction to Curb Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's Kaduna state
government wednesday extended its 24-hour restriction on the
movement of residents in the state's troubled capital to its
neighboring towns to curb the violence' s spill-over.
</P>
<P>
Towns near Kaduna city like Zaria, Kafanchan, Birnin-Gwari and
Kachia were ordered to observe the all-day curfew, when violence
were found in some of them, reported the Guardian, a leading
Nigerian newspaper Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The three-day violence started Monday in Kaduna city over
proposed implementation of Sharia was feared to have left some 300
people dead.
</P>
<P>
Uneasy calm prevailed in Kaduna city on Wednesday with a heavy
military and police presence on its streets.
</P>
<P>
But fresh eruption of violence in Kachia, Zaira had been
reported and the reports said they were quickly quelled down by
the police force on stand-by.
</P>
<P>
A state government spokesman said Wednesday that its government
"is holding series of meetings with religious leaders in an effort
to sustain the peace.
</P>
<P>
He said, "the government was aware of the hardship which the
restriction of movement will cause the people. that is why we hope
that by Thursday, or latest Friday, the order may be relaxed a
little". 
</P>
</TEXT>
