<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Murder of Burundian Refugees Political Motivated: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian police has
described an attack on a family of refugees from Burundi as a
politically motivated murder, a newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Five members of the same family living at Muyovosi camp in
Tanzania's western Kigoma Region were murdered on Wednesday night
last week in a grenade attack which is believed to have been
carried out by their own compatriots, the Guardian said.
</P>
<P>
According to Kigoma Regional Police Commander Placid Chaka,
preliminary investigation indicated that the murder is politically
motivated "because the assailants did not take anything from the
house."
</P>
<P>
"There are a lot of political divisions within the refugees in
the camps, " the police commander was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Jean Batungwanayo, a 55-year-old Burundian gynecologist who was
working at the refugee camp's medical center, his wife Frazia
Murekasoni, and their three children, were attacked and killed in
their house.
</P>
<P>
Batungwanayo was a brother of Leornard Nyangoma, leader of the
armed CNDD rebel group that is fighting the government troops in
Burundi, said the Guardian.
</P>
<P>
The police in Kigoma, which borders war-ravaged Burundi, had
until Wednesday arrested 14 Hutu refugees from Burundi in
connection with the murder.
</P>
<P>
According to Chaka, the police were taking no chance after
getting reports that villains responsible for the brutal murder
were seeking to behead the bodies and display their skulls as a
sign of warning to refugees at the Muyovosi camp.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Tanzanian government sources said Burundian rebels are
recruiting forces from refugee camps in western Tanzania and
slipping them out of the country for training.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania is hosting over 320,000 Burundian refugees who have
fled the six-year civil war in their homeland between Hutu rebels
and the Tutsi- dominated military. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
