<DOCNO> XIE20000224.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyclone Cuts Off Zimbabwe Fuel Supply Routes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Cyclone Eline cut off the fuel
supply route from Mozambique to Zimbabwe further worsening the
fuel crisis in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe oil companies Wednesday warned that the situation,
which had in recent weeks improved significantly, could plunge to
crisis because of the rain-bearing cyclone.
</P>
<P>
"While limited fuel imports are arriving via Beira-Feruka
pipeline, the Cyclone Eline, currently over Mozambique, has
adversely impacted on the supply of fuel to Zimbabwe," said the
oil Companies in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The cyclone, which has been described as the worst in 30 years,
is making it impossible for oil tankers to offload into the 33
kilometers pipeline to Mutare in east Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for South Africa's Unicorn Shipping, which operates
the only feeder station to the depot, said, "our ship is riding
out the storm offshore and there is no hope of anything docking
for the moment."
</P>
<P>
The unusually high water levels in South Africa, resulting in
floods, are also affecting the smooth flow of fuel by rail from
South Africa. Up to 70 percent of Zimbabwe's fuel comes through
the Port of Beira in Mozambique, and the remainder by rail from
South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Winding queues of petrol-powered vehicles had reapeared at most
service stations in Harare after a fortnight's break.
</P>
<P>
Fuel retailers are beginning to panic, expressing fears of
bankruptcy because of uncertainty as to when supplies would
return to normal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000224.0131 </DOCNO>
