<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bellemare Leads in Women's Short Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Annie Bellemare of Canada beat
American rivals Angela Nikodinov and Stacey Pensgen to finish atop
in the women's short program at the Four Continents Figure Skating
Championships in Osaka on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The 20-year-old Canadian staged an almost perfect performance
to receive the best marks in the required elements and
presentation.
</P>
<P>
"I have been working real hard all week long, and I am very
happy with what I did. I did kind of the best I could," said
Bellemare.
</P>
<P>
Nikodinov also skated almost error free to take second place,
while Pensgen fell at a triple flip to finish third.
</P>
<P>
"It's pretty hard, but I'm getting used to it," said Nikodinov,
the bronze medalist at the inaugural championships a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Defending champion Tatyana Malinina from Uzbekistan was
surprisingly fifth after needing a few steps between combination
jumps and ending a triple flip in a double. 
</P>
</TEXT>
