<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK, India to Develop Cooperation on IT </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong and India signed a
memorandum of understanding (MOU) on information technology and
services cooperation Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The MOU, the fifth sealed between the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR) and overseas countries, contemplates
an extensive range of cooperative activities, including exchanges
in commerce, industry and education, development of investment and
technology partnerships and the sharing of policy and regulatory
information.
</P>
<P>
"The signing of this MOU represents a significant step in the
buildup of closer cooperation between India and Hong Kong," said
Secretary for Information Technology and Broadcasting of the HKSAR
K. C. Kwong.
</P>
<P>
He noted that as the constraints of time and distance were
inexorably eroded by advances in information and
telecommunications technology, people from different parts of the
world could now aspire to work together in a seamless manner
wherever and whenever they are.
</P>
<P>
"Businesses are no longer facing competition only from their
immediate neighbors, but they are also no longer limited to
cooperation with those in their neighborhood," Kwong said.
</P>
<P>
"In the globally connected world of the 21st century,
international cooperation to face up to global competition is
therefore the key to success. And this cooperative spirit is
central to the MOU that we are signing today," Kwong said.
</P>
<P>
The HKSAR government has since May 1998 signed MOUs on IT
cooperation with Canada, Australia, Britain and Finland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
