<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Greatly Develop Border Economies in Ten Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government will
work for great economic growth in the border areas within a decade
by improving infrastructure and living standards there.
</P>
<P>
Mou Benli, deputy minister in charge of the State Ethnic
Affairs Commission, announced that his commission launched a
campaign today aiming at boosting border economies and helping the
poverty-stricken areas become rich, as part of the government
effort to develop the vast western regions of the country.
</P>
<P>
China's land border line is about 20,000 kilometers long, where
there are 135 counties including 107 ethnic minority autonomous
counties. Nearly half of the 20 million people who live in the
border areas are members of ethnic minority groups.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, the border areas reported a combined gross domestic
product (GDP) of 82.6 billion yuan (about 10 billion U.S. dollars),
accounting for 1.1 percent of China's GDP. The GDP per person
there was 3,983 yuan (about 480 U.S. dollars), 36.3 percent lower
than the nation's average.
</P>
<P>
By the same year, about 14 percent of the villages in the
border areas had no roads, 20 per cent had no access to
electricity and 55 percent had no running water.
</P>
<P>
"Economic development plays a key role in the stability and
development of China's border regions", the deputy minister said.
The campaign will focus on building roads, supplying electricity
and running water, getting rid of illiteracy, improving education
and disseminating sophisticated technology in these areas, he
added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000224.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most Indonesian People Disagree on Aceh's  Independence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, February 24 (Xinhua) -- About 88.5 percent respondents
disagreed on the independence of Indonesia's Aceh province and 72.
3 percent agreed on the government's plan to give the province a
special autonomy package, a survey result said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The survey result issued by the Center for the Study of
Development and Democracy (Cesda) said that 89.1 percent of
respondents also disagreed on the independence of Irian Jaya
province.
</P>
<P>
The Center said that the survey involved 1,247 respondents aged
above 18 years old and spreading in five big cities in the country,
namely Jakarta, Surabaya (East Java), Medan (North Sumatra),
Banjarmasin (West Kalimantan), Makassar (South Sulawesi).
</P>
<P>
There is a 3 percent margin of errors in the poll, the
institute said.
</P>
<P>
Most of respondents also regarded that the main causes of the
separatist movements which have been taking place in Indonesia
were the social and economical gap between Java island and out-
side Java as well as the weakness of the central government.
</P>
<P>
Respondents however agreed and backed the government policy to
soon implement special autonomy bill in Aceh Province in a bid to
calm down separatist movement there.
</P>
<P>
Aceh is the most western province of Indonesia, which has been
demanding for independence and separating from the unitary state
of Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The Free Aceh Movement (GAM), an armed separatist group in Aceh
led by Tengku Abdullah Syafei, has been fighting against the
central government for independence since 1976.
</P>
<P>
However, President Abdurrahman Wahid has insisted that he would
not tolerate any separatist movement, warning that his side would
not hesitate to take stern measures against those trying to
separate from the unitary state of Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The central government has pledged to immediately implement the
special autonomy bill for Aceh Province, which has been approved
by the House of Representatives (DPR), and stage the human right
tribunal against those believed to have been involved in human
right abuse and atrocities there.
</P>
<P>
The human right trial is scheduled to be started in early March,
under which some of the Indonesian military (TNI) personnel will
be brought to justice.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, hundreds of Acehnese separatist reportedly have
surrendered to the local police.
</P>
<P>
It was also reported that the number of the surrenders keeps
increasing while TNI headquarters said the GAM commander has been
injured and "dying" in a gun fighting in Pidie regency couples
days ago.
</P>
<P>
However, there was no independent confirmation on the fate of
the GAM commander, news on the commander's "dying" was denied by
the GAM. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000224.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Writethru: Volcano Erupts, Thousands Fleeing Away </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Mayon Volcano in the
southeastern part of the Philippines erupted Thursday morning,
sending lava fountains and huge columns of smoke in the sky as
local residents fled their homes to evacuation centers.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Institute of Volcanology and Seismology (
Phivolcs) said in a bulletin that at 08:26 a.m. local time (0026
GMT) an explosion type earthquake was recorded, which was followed
3 minutes later by pyroclastic flow pouring down the Bonga Gully
at the southeastern side of the mountain.
</P>
<P>
Raymundo Punongbayan, director of Phivolcs, said the villages
along the mountain's southeastern side faces the greatest threats,
because the southeastern crater wall had collapsed in previous
eruptions.
</P>
<P>
That is why lava and other pyroclastic materials that Mayon
spewed out are dumped towards that direction, he added.
</P>
<P>
The 2,462-meter Mayon Volcano has erupted at least 40 times
since 1616 and its latest major eruption was in 1993, which killed
some 70 persons.
</P>
<P>
Mt. Mayon is also one of 22 most active volcanoes in the
Philippines, a country which has more than 200 volcanoes
distributed in its whole territory.
</P>
<P>
Phivolcs said it raised Mt. Mayon's alert level twice Thursday,
first early Thursday morning from Three to Four, and then at 9 a.m.
from Four to Five.
</P>
<P>
Alert Level 4 means the volcano starts spewing lava from the
summit, causing lava flows down while Level 5 indicates eruption
activity, Phivolcs explained.
</P>
<P>
Fortunately, no one was reported hurt yet, but residents within
the 8-kilometer danger zone of the volcano were also advised to
evacuate.
</P>
<P>
Volcanologists warned that a more violent explosion could occur
at any time.
</P>
<P>
The volcano, lying some 300 kilometers southeast of Manila in
Albay province, on Wednesday night were seen spewing its first
fountain of lava, a blast that occurred for a few minutes.
</P>
<P>
Volcanologists said this was among the initial signs of a
forthcoming major blast, following days of lava flow.
</P>
<P>
Ash falls were already reported in the nearby towns of Camalig,
Ligao and Guinobatan in Albay province.
</P>
<P>
As on Thursday afternoon, some 10,000 local residents have fled
the immediate area, but authorities urged thousands more living in
villages up to eight miles away from the crater to evacuate.
</P>
<P>
Classes were suspended in schools in Legazpi city in Albay
province and were used as evacuation centers.
</P>
<P>
Reports said Philippine Vice President Gloria Macapagal-Arroyo
had arrived in Legazpi, 10 kilometers away from Mayon, on Thursday
noon to assess the conditions of the evacuees.
</P>
<P>
Arroyo said there would be enough food and provisions for Mayon
refugees housed in the evacuation centers.
</P>
<P>
According to Arroyo, who is also Secretary of the Department of
Social Welfare and Development, the department has stockpile of
food and resources enough for 1,000 families in 20 weeks, or about
five months.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Arroyo had cautioned local government officials to
submit hasty reports, saying that releases of food and provisions
would be based on their reports.
</P>
<P>
Arroyo, who landed at the Pili Airport in the neighboring North
Camarines province, motored to Legazpi City and visited various
evacuation centers, where she talked with local government
officials regarding evacuees problems.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Wednesday, evacuees have complained of poor
provisions in some evacuation centers, including the lack of
toilets and water.
</P>
<P>
Albay Governor Al Bichara have reportedly ordered the
construction of emergency toilet facilities and the repair of
faucet connections and pumps in those evacuation centers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000224.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices End Lower on Singapore Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Share prices closed lower on
the Singapore Stock Market Thursday on profit-taking after a brief
reprieve on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Index (STI) lost 14.03 points to
end at 2,123.67 points, down from the intraday-high of 2,152.41
points early in the morning session.
</P>
<P>
The total turnover contracted to 438.93 million units valued at
729.96 million Singapore dollars (425.90 million U.S. dollars).
Declining issues edged out advancers by 251 to 94 with 163
counters unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The larger block was the 27.68 million parcel by Unisteel which
was transacted at 0.515 Singapore dollars per share. It was
followed by Goldtrn which had a turnover of 21.84 million units.
MMI was the next with 20.34 million counters changing hands.
</P>
<P>
PacCent was the biggest gainer of the day soaring up by 370
cents to close at 29.40 Singapore dollars. SPH and SPH 100 surged
up 90 cents to finish at 31.80 and 31.70 Singapore dollars
respectively. Bukit Sem and SembLog picked up 50 cents to end at
15.00 and 8.80 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, DBS headed descent of the day sinking 60 cents
to end at 20.60 Singapore dollars. OUB shed 45 cents to finish at
7.65 Singapore dollars. UOB and Venture retreated 40 cents to
close at 11.30 and 25.10 Singapore dollars respectively.
</P>
<P>
Dealers noted that the market initially rose as technology
stocks were boosted by the record overnight closing of the U.S.
Nasdaq market.
</P>
<P>
However, they said, shares gave up early gains as later selling
pushed the STI down.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said buying confidence remained patchy, because of the
sharp falls suffered by the local bourses in earlier sessions.
</P>
<P>
Brokers also noted that the news that Singapore's GDP grew by 5.
4 percent in 1999 was largely ignored by the market as it fell
within expectation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
