<HEADLINE> U.S. Bank to Finance Indian Power Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Export-Import Bank
(Exim) has signed an agreement with India's Power Finance
Corporation (PFC) to collaborate on financing up to 500 million U.
S. dollars for power projects in the country.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Exim Chairman James Harmon said Thursday that the long-
term partnership with the PFC is under the India Energy
Partnership Program, implemented by the U.S. Energy Association
and U.S. Agency for International Development.
</P>
<P>
The financing is aimed to support Indian purchases of clean
energy, high-efficiency and other kinds of U.S.-made power
equipment and services.
</P>
<P>
This was the first loan approved by U.S. Exim after the United
States imposed sanctions on India after its nuclear tests in 1998.
</P>
