<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Some Chief Genocide Suspects May Be Tried in Rwanda: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
International Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda (ICTR) is examining the
possibility of having some trials of chief genocide suspects heard
in the Rwandan capital Kigali, Tanzanian media reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A chamber in the Supreme Court of Rwanda was being refurbished
for the purpose, ICTR Chief Prosecutor Carla Del Ponte said
Wednesday in Tanzania's northern town of Arusha where the U.N.
court is based.
</P>
<P>
The intention was to get the Rwandan public to be adequately
informed on trial proceedings on what had happened to their
country, the Daily News quoted the prosecutor as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Rwandan government also wishes to have some case hearing in
Kigali.
</P>
<P>
But ICTR is not under any pressure from anybody to do so, said
Del Ponte.
</P>
<P>
The former Swiss federal prosecutor said she was convinced that
the holding of some trials of chief suspects in places where
crimes were committed will have positive effect in pursuing
justice.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. court has handed down only five verdicts since it was
set up six years ago to try leading architects and perpetrators
involved in the 1994 genocide, in which an estimated 500,000
Rwandan Tutsis and moderate Hutus were killed.
</P>
<P>
The court has 38 chief suspects in custody in Tanzania.
Rwanda's jam- packed prisons hold 125,000 lesser suspects awaiting
trial.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda has been conducting its own genocide trials and has so
far tried1, 500 lesser suspects and executed 22 convicts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
