<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Deregulate Prices of Oil Products by End of 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria will deregulate the
prices of petroleum products before the end of this year despite
strong opposition, president's chief economic adviser Philip
Asiodu said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Such deregulation is necessary because the Nigerian government
simply could not afford the large amount of subsidy to press the
petroleum price down, the News Agency of Nigeria quoted Asiodu as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The presidential adviser said that the terrible economic
situation left by several decades of military misrule will be
changed as President Olusegun Obasanjo administration is committed
to rapid development of the economy and improvement in the quality
of lives of all citizens.
</P>
<P>
The progress was under way through its well-thought out program
like the poverty alleviation and economic restructuring in the
oil-producing country, Asiodu said.
</P>
<P>
The agricultural sector will be given the greatest priority for
both poverty reduction in the rural areas as well as the general
improvement of the economy, he added. 
</P>
