<HEADLINE> Eritrean President Meets U.S. Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Eritrean President Isaias
Afwerki discussed with U.S. special envoy Anthony Lake the status
of the peace plan initiated by the Organization of African Unity
(OAU) in Asmara on Thursday morning, the Eritrean News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The report did not go into the details of their meeting.
</P>
<P>
Lake, former U.S. National Security Adviser, arrived in the
Eritrean capital on Wednesday night in a fresh bid to find a
solution to the border war between Eritrea and Ethiopia. He is
expected to travel on to Addis Ababa later Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. envoy visited the Horn of Africa region several times
last year to mediate an end to the 22-month-old conflict.
</P>
<P>
The Eritrean government is also expecting Ahmed Ouyahia,
Algerian Foreign Minister and OAU envoy, in Asmara this Friday.
Ouyahia is currently in Addis Ababa as part of a mission to the
region to push the implementation of the OAU peace plan.
</P>
<P>
Eritrea has officially accepted the OAU peace package while
Ethiopia has objected to the plan, the official Eritrean News
Agency said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Asmara said Wednesday that fresh fighting had broken
out at the Burie (Assab) front on the border with Ethiopia after
some nine month lull.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopian government spokesperson Selome Taddesse confirmed
that there were skirmishes at the Burie front in northeast of
Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
However, both sides declined to revealed their casualties in
the fighting which stopped quickly.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that this does not mean the Ethio-Eritrean war
has restarted.
</P>
<P>
During the dry season last year, a heavy round of fighting on
three fronts along the 1,000-km border line left tens of thousands
of soldiers dead in bloody trench warfare.  The two neighbors
took to arms in early May 1998 over the disputed border. 
</P>
</TEXT>
