<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Confirms Fighting With Eritrea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian government
spokesperson Selome Taddesse confirmed that there were skirmishes
between Ethiopia and Eritrea at the Bure front in northeast of
Ethiopia on Wednesday morning and accused Eritrea for starting the
attack.
</P>
<P>
"The skirmish stopped very quickly, and nothing happened in
that region today," the official said on Thursday. She declined to
mention casualties on the Ethiopian side.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that some 2,500 troops from Ethiopia and
Eritrean troops were involved in the battle which took place near
Assab, a port city of Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
Selome said Eritrea was trying to leave people an impression
that Ethiopia is not willing to have political settlement of the
conflict.
</P>
<P>
She said Eritrea tried to ask the world community to impose
pressure on Ethiopia as Ahmed Ouyahia, special envoy of Chairman
of the Organization of African Unity, Algerian President Abdul
Aziz Bouteflika, is here for talks with the Ethiopian government
over the peaceful settlement of the Ethio- Eritrean conflict.
</P>
<P>
Reliable sources said that U.S President special envoy Athony
Lake arrived here last night to mediate the conflict.
</P>
<P>
Selome expressed belief that the latest skirmish between
Ethiopia and Eritrea would not have any influence over the
settlement of the conflict.
</P>
<P>
Eritrean presidential adviser Yemane Ghebremeskel was quoted
by Reuters as saying that some 1,500 troops were involved in the
fighting on Wednesday and about 200 Ethiopian soldiers were killed
or wounded.
</P>
<P>
So far there's no report about which side started the fresh
fighting after about a year of relative quite.  
</P>
