<HEADLINE> Chinese Consumer Prices Surged in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Consumer prices jumped up by
nearly one percentage point in January, according to official
sources.
</P>
<P>
Figures released by the National Bureau of Statistics (NBS)
today show that consumer prices and retail prices in January rose
by 0.9 percent and one percent over December.
</P>
<P>
The surge of consumer prices was higher than the 0.2 percent in
January last year and the 0.7 percent in January 1998. Retail
prices were 2.1 percent lower than the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
NBS said that the surge of consumer prices in January was due
to the holiday season and an increase in housing, water,
electricity, fuel gas prices.
</P>
<P>
Local economists say that as industrial production continued to
grow at 8.9 percent in January, consumer demand will increase in
the next few months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
