<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Computers Monitor Tax Evasion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 24 (Xinhua) -- China's taxation departments
successfully solved more than 30,000 tax evasion cases last year
facilitated by computerized taxation management and supervision
systems.
</P>
<P>
Computers have greatly improved work efficiency and curb tax
evasion crimes.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, Chinese tax collectors monitored some 17 million
Chinese taxpayers. Computers were used to collect 710 billion yuan
of taxes in 1999, or 70 percent of industrial and commercial tax
revenues across the country.
</P>
<P>
Taxation departments nationwide were equipped with 200,000
computers by the end of last year, with 120,000 enterprises using
an anti-forgery system to tighten tax collection.
</P>
<P>
The anti-forgery system, using a special code to read computer-
printed invoices, proved successful in preventing invoice
counterfeiting.
</P>
<P>
Jin Renqing, director of the State Administration of Taxation,
said the computer systems were first applied to value-added tax
invoices worth more than 100,000 yuan (about 12,000 U.S. dollars).
Jin called for more taxation officials to learn how to use the
computer systems.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
