<HEADLINE> People Urged to Protect China's Relics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 24 (Xinhua) -- China encourages people from
all walks of life to contribute to protecting the country's
archaeological treasures while the Chinese government continues to
play a major role in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Wenbin, who heads the State Cultural Heritage
Administration (SCHA), said today at a national conference that he
hopes to establish new laws for protecting relics. Zhang stressed
that all Chinese should join hands to safeguard its national
treasures.
</P>
<P>
SCHA will give awards to those who help to protect China's
relics, Zhang said, hoping that the Hong Kong-based China Heritage
Fund will help collect more overseas donations.
</P>
<P>
Zhang warned localities against selling off national treasures.
</P>
<P>
Latest statistics show that China has about 400,000 relics.
Fourteen of these such as the Great Wall and the Forbidden City
are now on the World Heritage list.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,900 museums across the country have preserved nearly 12
million relics. 
</P>
