<DOCNO> XIE20000224.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait to Probe Possible Link Between Gulf War and Certain Diseases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait is to conduct a
study to determine the possible link between the 1991 Gulf war and
the higher incidence of some diseases observed here including
cancer and cardiovascular disease.
</P>
<P>
"Observations are very alarming which need studies to see if it
is with or without any roots to the Iraqi invasion and occupation
of Kuwait," said Dr. Ahmad Al-Shatti, secretary general of the
Kuwait Medical Association, in an interview with local English
daily Arab Times published Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The situation deserves all costs to monitor people who were
exposed to seven months of inhaling smoke from oil fires resulted
from the burning of over 700 oil wells by the Iraqi troops which
invaded Kuwait in August 1990, he said.
</P>
<P>
Besides polluted air, there may have been unclean food and
destroyed sewage system, he added.
</P>
<P>
There is "no doubt that there are quite a good number of victims
of the invasion," he said.
</P>
<P>
Doctors have noticed an increasing number of cancer cases and
even leukemia among children. "Every year we record around 30 cases
plus or minus of lung cancer," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwaiti official said they just want to understand why there
are more cases of leukemia among children and why cancer cases of
the mouth, throat, esophagus and stomach are also growing.
</P>
<P>
Although a Gulf War-related syndrome was reported among U.S.
soldiers who took part in the Operation Desert Storm in 1991, no
diseases definitedly connected with the war have so far been
pronounced. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
