<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Conservatives in Iran Pin Hope on Rafsanjani to Strike Power Balance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Suffering a severe setback in
Friday's parliamentary elections, conservatives in Iran are pinning
their hope on former President Hashemi Rafsanjani to make a balance
between conservatives and reformists in the new Majlis
(parliament).
</P>
<P>
"Rafsanjani is indeed the best choice as next Majlis speaker as
none other parliament member can match him in experience and
competence," the conservative daily Tehran Times said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The paper, by mentioning Rafsanjani's experience as Majlis
speaker in 1980-89 and president in 1989-97, claimed that
Rafsanjani has won a seat in the new parliament.
</P>
<P>
However, the official Islamic Republic News Agency on Thursday
quoted the latest statistics as saying that Rafsanjani ranked the
28th in Tehran constituency by gaining 24.86 percent of the 2.789
million votes so far counted, less than the minimum 25 percent to
enter the Majlis.
</P>
<P>
Although the reformists have seized a majority of seats in the
parliament, they are surely facing an uphill task in the next
legislature for several reasons, the most pressing one is the lack
of unity among members of the May 23 Front, Tehran Times said.
</P>
<P>
The 18 parties comprising the "May 23 Front" in support of
President Mohammad Khatami hold divergent views on some issues,
said the paper.
</P>
<P>
It said that there are serious differences between the two major
elements of the front, the Assembly of Combatant Clergy (ACC) led
by former speaker Mehdi Karrubi and the Islamic Iran Participation
Front (IIPF) led by Mohammad Reza Khatami, the president's younger
brother.
</P>
<P>
In this light, many senior politicians believe that Rafsanjani
will be the best choice for the next speaker, who can maintain
unity in the May 23 Front, it said.
</P>
<P>
Iran's reformists have won a landslide victory in the Friday
polls, by bagging 137 seats out of the total of 191 determined.
Meanwhile, 27 top winners in Tehran constituency are from the
reformist lists, though no final result has been announced yet
about the fate of the 30 seats in the capital city.
</P>
<P>
But top reformist leaders have ruled out the possibility of
electing Rafsanjani as the future Majlis speaker since they
strongly opposed his participation in the polling.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the paper also said that the IIPF has planned to ask
President Khatami to reshuffle the cabinet formed by reformists and
pro-Rafsanjani centralists, who maintain close ties with the
conservatives.
</P>
<P>
Top party officials of the IIPF held a meeting just after their
sweeping victory in the 6th Majlis elections and decided to ask
Khatami to sack at least three ministers, the daily quoted some
sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
The three ministers are Education Minister Hossein Mozaffar,
Construction Minister Jihad Mohammad Saeedi-Kiya, and Minister of
Economy Hossein Namazi, whom the daily termed as independents.
</P>
<P>
However, the daily did not elaborate on who would replace the
three ministers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
