<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Govt. Orders to Shoot on Sight Pipeline Vandals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government
Wednesday ordered oil pipeline vandals be "shot on sight", the
News Agency of Nigeria reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The order was given to the police following complaints that the
 lingering fuel shortage in some parts of the country was caused
by pipeline vandalization.
</P>
<P>
Layiwola Sanmi, the area manager of the Nigerian National
Petroleum Corporation in Ogun State, said Wednesday that all
efforts made by the corporation to stop the vandals had not
yielded fruit, hence its decision to approach the government and
police for help.
</P>
<P>
According to Sanmi, the "shot on sight" order was given
directly by President Olusegun Obasanjo.
</P>
<P>
"No doubt, vandalization is our greatest problem," the manager
said, noting that for any line vandalized, it costs the Nigerian
national petroleum corporation between 1.2 million to 1.6 million
naira (12,000 to 16,000 U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
