<HEADLINE> Russia Condemns Attack on its Mission in Poland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister Igor
Ivanov Thursday condemned Wednesday's attack on the Russian
consulate in Poznan, Poland as "a hooligan action."
</P>
<P>
Pro-Chechen protesters tore off and burnt a Russian flag, and
raised a Chechen flag over the consulate building. They drew a
swastika on the wall of the consulate, claiming they are members
of the "Free Caucasus Committee", the Itar-Tass news agency
reported, noting that Polish police did not intervene.
</P>
<P>
"This was a hooligan action, which deserves the most vigorous
condemnation, and we shall address a protest to the Polish
authorities," Tass quoted Ivanov as saying in Minsk, Belarus.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov arrived in Minsk Wednesday to attend a joint meeting of
the Collegium of the Belarussian and Russian Foreign Ministries.
</P>
<P>
Demonstrations were also held Wednesday before the buildings of
the Russian embassy in Warsaw and the Russian consulates in Krakow
and Gdansk.
</P>
<P>
Tass said that the protests, organized by Chechen emissaries
and several Polish anti-Russian organizations, were timed for the
56th anniversary of the start of mass deportation of ethnic
Chechens to Central Asia and Siberia during the Second World War.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
