<DOCNO> XIE20000224.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NASA, Boeing Dispute Over Cost Overruns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, February 23 (Xinhua) -- A report released
Wednesday said the National Aeronautics and Space Administration (
NASA) will keep closer tabs on Boeing Co. due to nearly one
billion U.S. dollars in cost overruns on the International Space
Station (ISS) project.
</P>
<P>
The report by NASA Inspector General Roberta L. Gross blamed
much of the overruns in the 9.8-billion-dollar contract on
Boeing's 1996 acquisition of pieces of Rockwell International Corp.
and the 1997 merger with McDonnell Douglas Corp.
</P>
<P>
"Neither Boeing nor its Space and Communications Group promptly
notified NASA about the potential cost increases due to Boeing's
reorganization," the report said.
</P>
<P>
Boeing spokeswoman Kari Allen said Wednesday that the company
had cooperated with the audit and had already instituted a number
of changes recommended in the report.
</P>
<P>
"The International Space Station is huge developmental program.
We've never done this before," Allen said. "Overruns are never
welcome in any program, but in developmental programs you
certainly can expect it."
</P>
<P>
The Boeing Co. is the prime contractor for the space station
project. With 150 other sub-contractors and other firms, according
to industry sources, Boeing has completed the U.S. laboratory
module and the Unity module, which has been in orbit since
December 15, 1998. It is also working on computer and life-support
systems for the station.
</P>
<P>
The United States is one of 16 nations that has pledged to
support the International Space Station, which could welcome its
first crew as early as next year. The station, which will provide
a permanent space laboratory and habitat, is scheduled to complete
in 2004, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The ISS project has been plagued by problems due to delays by
the cash-strapped Russian Space Agency.
</P>
<P>
NASA said it is awaiting the delivery and launch of a Russian
control module, and it will launch its own control module by the
end of this year if Russia does not follow through on its
obligations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
