<DOCNO> XIE20000224.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Continues Air Strikes on Rebels in Southern Chechnya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The Russian federal air force
continued air strikes Thursday on militants in the southern
mountains of the breakaway republic of Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
Sukhoi-24 front-line bombers, Sukhoi-25 attack aircraft and Mi-
24 helicopter gunships hit rebel positions in Argun and Vedeno
gorges and the area of Shatoi, the Interfax news agency reported,
quoting the headquarters of the federal forces in the North
Caucasus.
</P>
<P>
More than 120 combat missions were flown a day earlier,
destroying 11 rebel strongholds, four fortified areas, two large
caliber machine-gun positions, one air defense installation, one
communication center, four fortified firing positions and two
trucks, according to preliminary estimates.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the federal forces brought in more reinforcements to
the southern mountains in the wake of ferocious rebel attempts to
break across the border into neighboring Georgia, Interfax said.
</P>
<P>
Mi-8 helicopters flew over 200 troops and 1.5 ton of hardware
Wednesday to the border near the village of Omi-Chu, scene of
fierce fighting Tuesday, after three Russian border guards were
killed when Chechen militants tried to fight their way from the
Argun gorge into Georgia.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday marked the 56th anniversary of the start of mass
deportation of ethnic Chechens to Central Asia and Siberia during
the Second World War. Security was beefed up across Russia and
especially inside the breakaway republic, amid reports of planned
terrorist attacks by Chechen rebels.
</P>
<P>
The much-feared attacks did not materialize, but the
administrative border between Chechnya and the neighboring Russian
constituent republics is expected to remain closed.
</P>
<P>
Authorities said that the measures were only temporary, and the
border checkpoints could reopen as early as on Thursday afternoon,
although any new tension could postpone the reopening.
</P>
<P>
Russia launched the military operation against the rebels last
September following two waves of armed Chechen incursions into
neighboring Daghestan and a series of apartment bombings, also
blamed on Chechen separatists, that killed over 300 people in
Moscow and two other cities.
</P>
<P>
The rebels have been driven out of the Chechen capital of
Grozny and other main populated settlements. The bulk of the
remaining militants, estimated at 5,000-6,000, now concentrate in
the southern mountains. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
