<DOCNO> XIE20000224.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WWF Welcomes Poland's Move on Vistula River Dam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The World Wide Fund for Nature
(WWF) has welcomed the Polish cabinet's recent move to insist that
an independent technical expert group examine all concerns and
alternatives before it makes a final decision on whether to build
a new 250-million-dollar dam on the Vistula River.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released here Wednesday, WWF Director General
Claude Martin congratulated the Polish government on its
enlightened decision and repeated the WWF's offer to help
facilitate technical assistance and finance for the assessment of
alternative schemes to solve the problems of the existing
Wloclawek dam.
</P>
<P>
In response to the announcement by Polish Minister of Finance
and Deputy Prime Minister Leszek Balcerowicz on Tuesday night on
Polish National Radio, the WWF's Program Coordinator for Poland
Ireneusz Chojnacki said, "This decision could be a very important
turning point for Poland."
</P>
<P>
"It could make Poland the front-runner among EU accession
countries in a new approach to environmental management," he added.
"This is especially significant in the face of the European
Commission's ongoing concerns over Poland's readiness for early
accession due to their poor environmental record."
</P>
<P>
The WWF said that it had informed the president of the European
Commission of this positive development. It is calling for support
from the European Commission and other financial institutions and
bilateral donors to create a Sustainable Development Plan, in
collaboration with the Polish Government, that will provide
benefits for the whole Vistula valley.
</P>
<P>
The WWF has been endeavoring to reach a formal Memorandum of
Understanding with the Polish Environment Ministry to serve as a
basis for the development of this plan since September 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
