<DOCNO> XIE20000224.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korean Current Account Surplus Down Last Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, February 24 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's current-account
surplus plunged to 25 billion U.S. dollars in 1999 from the
previous year's 40.5 billion due to increased imports caused by
its economic recovery, the Bank of Korea said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The 1998 figure was the largest in South Korea's history.
</P>
<P>
Exports led by key items such as autos, semiconductors,
machinery and heavy and chemical goods hit 145.49 billion dollars
last year while imports totaled 111.68 billion dollars due to oil
and spare parts imports, up 29 percent from 1998.
</P>
<P>
The surplus amounted to 28.72 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the service account ended up l.01 billion dollars in
the red because of increases in overseas spending by travelers,
payment of royalties and consulting fees.
</P>
<P>
Current transfers surplus declined to 1.95 billion dollars last
year from 3.35 billion dollars in 1998 due to reduced remittances
from overseas.
</P>
<P>
The capital account registered 580 million dollars of net
inflow in 1999 from 3.25 billion dollars of net outflow in 1998,
with foreign stock investment funds offsetting repayment of
various foreign loans, including those to the International
Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
South Korea borrowed 58 billion dollars from the IMF in
December 1997 after it was gripped by a financial crisis caused by
corporate bankruptcies and bad loans of financial institutions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
