<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Turkish Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Turkish newspapers on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Milliyet (National):
</P>
<P>
-- In response to a predicted German request for Turkey to free
the detained mayors of three Southeastern cities, Ankara said on
Wednesday that the detentions are internal affairs of Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The mayors were arrested on the weekend for allegedly supporting
the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party, which has been fighting since
1984 for an independent Kurdish state in southeast.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the detentions could lead to a new crisis between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Hurriyet (Freedom):
</P>
<P>
-- The Turkish police Wednesday detained 17 protestors in
Diyarbakir who were demonstrating against the detentions of the
three pro-Kurdish mayors and calling for their release.
</P>
<P>
One of the arrested mayors was from Diyarbakir, Turkey's largest
Kurdish city in the southeast.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Daily News:
</P>
<P>
-- Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit said Wednesday that the results
of the recently-held Iranian elections will be instrumental in
improving relations between Turkey and Iran.
</P>
<P>
He said that "the sweeping victory of the reformists in Iran
will be conducive to a more contemporary and moderate Islam in the
country." 
</P>
</TEXT>
