<DOCNO> XIE20000224.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Peace Envoy Arrives in Cairo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 24 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Mideast envoy Dennis Ross
arrived here early Thursday for a visit to Egypt as part of his
ongoing tour of the Middle East region.
</P>
<P>
He is due to hold talks with senior Egyptian officials on means
of pushing forward the stalled peace process, Egypt's Middle East
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Ross, who arrived in Jerusalem Monday, met Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak earlier in the day and Palestinian National
Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat on Tuesday evening, but no
progress was made towards relaunching the Israeli-Palestinian
talks.
</P>
<P>
"There is a lot of work to be done and the best way to do that
is to get on with it,"Ross said in Jerusalem Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"We need to resolve some of the remaining problems with regard
to the interim issues, we have to get on with the final status
negotiations," he added.
</P>
<P>
Peace talks between Israel and the Palestinians ground to a halt
two weeks ago after a dispute over a long-delayed Israeli troop
withdrawal from the West Bank under the Sharm el Sheikh memorandum
caused the two sides to miss the February 13 deadline for working
out a framework agreement for the final peace.
</P>
<P>
However, Ross said the talks would continue amid a desire on
both sides to break the impasse.
</P>
<P>
"What I have seen is a clear desire on the part of both sides to
find a way to move forward," Ross told journalists after a meeting
of over two hours with Arafat in Ramallah on the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, the first Arab country to sign a peace treaty with
Israel, has been a key mediator in peace negotiations between the
Jewish state and other Arab states and the Palestinians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000224.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Deputy Prime Minister to Visit Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Russian Deputy Prime Minister
Ilya Klebanov will pay a two-day official visit to Turkey starting
on February 28, Turkish Daily News reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Klebanov will reportedly be received by Turkish President
Suleyman Demirel and also meet with the defense and foreign
ministers.
</P>
<P>
The issues to be covered during Klebanov's visit range from
bilateral relations, particularly on economic issues, to regional
policies on the Caucasus and the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
As Russian state and private companies are very interested in
Turkey's numerous military tenders, Klebanov is expected to discuss
military bids as well as energy issues during his visit.
</P>
<P>
Turkey meets its gas demands by buying natural gas from Russia,
and this subject is also expected to be discussed.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the existing pipeline through the Balkans, Russia
is constructing another pipeline, the Blue Stream project, under
the Black Sea to supply gas to Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
