<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerians Urged to Leave Religious Bigotry, Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian President Olusegun
Obasanjo told the nation that Nigeria must leave the line of
religious bigotry and violence if it does want to become great
again, the Guardian newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The president blamed those taking part in the violence in the
northern Kaduna city as "highly unpatriotic", as they tend to deny
the country the current precious opportunity to develop.
</P>
<P>
"What have we really gained from the horror of Kaduna?
Absolutely nothing, except wanton destruction, loss of mutual
trust and belief in the merits of tolerance", Obasanjo  said in a
nationwide broadcast speech Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We must return to tolerance, constitutionality, decency and
good neighborliness. Extremism in religion, nationalism, or in any
other human emotion is self-destructive in addition to possibly
destroying its victim," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The international community is beginning to regain its
confidence in our nation. We cannot afford to lose the
considerable amount of goodwill that has greeted our transition to
the democratic governance," said the president.
</P>
<P>
"We need that goodwill to sustain our efforts at reconstructing
the country and improving the economic prosperity of every man,
woman and child in this country," he added.
</P>
<P>
According to unconfirmed reports, the death toll had hit 300 by
late Wednesday during the violent clashes between the Moslems and
Christians in Kaduna over the proposed implementation of the
Islamic Sharia law, despite the deployment of troops in the Kaduna
State.
</P>
<P>
To curb the fresh violence sparkled in areas near Kaduna city,
the Kaduna State government Wednesday had extended the all-day
movement restriction to several other cities near the state's
capital.
</P>
<P>
Heavy presence of police and soldiers were seen on the streets
of Kaduna guarding a highly fragile tranquility Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
