<HEADLINE> Shell to Invest $8.6Bln in Nigeria in 5 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Shell Petroleum Development
Company has announced a planed 8.6 billion-U.S. dollar new
investment in Nigeria for the coming five years, media here
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Shell is embarking on an integrated long-term program to develop
both oil and associated gas reserves in Nigeria, John Barry, the
company's development director, said in Lagos Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
One-third of the investment would be expended on operation
costs while the remaining would be spent on capital projects,
Barry was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said the new investment, which would be funded through the
traditional joint venture mechanism, is aimed to enhance the
development in indigenous market and achieve a 40 percent
indigenous staff positioning within the next four years in
Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The huge investment plan of Shell would provide a significant
workload for contractors to always comply with the company's
business principles, he added.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Shell spent 1.9 billion dollars in
Nigeria's oil industry last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
