<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coliform Endangers Siberian Tiger's Life </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Coliform has been blamed for
death of Duoduo and sending Meimei into a coma, two female
Siberian tigers in Shenyang in northeast China's Liaoning Province.
</P>
<P>
Vets said the two tigers, brought from Harbin, capital of
northeast China's Heilongjiang Province, fell sick after eating
frozen meat that went bad.
</P>
<P>
Duoduo and Meimei, both in their twenties, were vulnerable to
sickness. Cold weather worsened their condition. The average life
expectancy for tigers is around 20 years.
</P>
<P>
Zookeepers said that they had bought 800 kilograms of meat for
the animals before the Chinese Lunar New Year which fell on
February 5. The tigers developed diarrhea and vomiting after
eating the rotten meat on February 10.
</P>
<P>
Siberian tigers are among the top ten most endangered species
in the world, with only around 300 remaining in the wild. The
Shenyang Zoo has bred and raised 13 Siberian tigers. One of the
tigers had a cesarean which attracted nationwide publicity.
</P>
</TEXT>
