<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Schoolchildren in China Overworked: Survey (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 24 (Xinhua) -- "It's me who carries the
heaviest schoolbag/It's me who has the most homework/and it's me
who is the first to get up and the last to go to bed." So reads a
popular song set to new lyrics by primary and middle school
students in China.
</P>
<P>
An official survey shows that a half of primary and middle
school students are overworked and do not get enough sleep.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the National Committee for Young Pioneers' Work and
the China Juvenile Research Center conducted a survey among a
group of urban and rural students aged between 6-14 years on hours
spent on homework and in the classroom and how many hours they
slept each night.
</P>
<P>
The survey revealed that 67.2 percent of urban children and 45.
6 percent of rural students aged between 6-8 spent more hours on
homework a day than the half an hour regulation; 36.8 percent of
students in the city and 26.3 percent in the countryside aged
between 9-12 spent more hours than the one hour regulation; 20.6
percent of junior high school students in cities and 20.1 percent
of their counterparts in the countryside spent more hours on than
the hour and a half regulation.
</P>
<P>
These students also spent more hours in schools than what is
required according to relevant state standards.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey, 46.9 percent of these students did not
get the required nine-hour sleep per day, 26.1 percent slept eight
hours a day, 12.6 percent seven hours a day and 8.2 percent less
than seven hours.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000224.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Schoolchildren in China Overworked: Survey (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A 1998 survey conducted by the National Bureau of Statistics in
10 provinces revealed that primary and middle school students
stayed at school for an average of 8.8 hours a day. It took two
hours for 80 percent of primary school students to finish their
daily homework but for junior high school students it took more
than two hours.
</P>
<P>
For senior high school students, homework was escalating due to
the increasing pressure to get high grades and pass the national
examination for entering university or college. There is also
enormous pressure on teachers as well.
</P>
<P>
Another survey by the China Juvenile Research Center and the
Beijing Normal University indicates that only 8.4 percent primary
school students surveyed like school, while 10.7 percent of junior
high school students are of the same opinion. Extra-curricular
activities such as scientific experiments, working on the computer
and reading are the three most enjoyed activities for these
students.
</P>
<P>
Some experts pointed out that many schools and parents are
pushing their children to the limits to perform even better at
school, depriving them of their necessary sleep.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that it is wrong to deprive children of sleep so
they can spend more time on homework and studies, and call for an
end to the practice.  
</P>
</TEXT>
