<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Secretary of Energy Ends Visit to Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 24 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of Energy Bill
Richardson left here Thursday morning for Kuwait after winding up a
visit to Egypt for promoting bilateral energy cooperation.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Richardson held talks with Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak, Prime Minister Atef Obeid, Minister of Electricity
and Energy Ali el-Saeedi and Minister of Petroleum Sameh Fahmi on
ways of boosting bilateral cooperation especially in the fields of
power, non-conventional energy and oil.
</P>
<P>
While describing the talks as "a strong impetus to cooperation
between the two countries," Ali el-Saeedi said during the meeting
they discussed projects which the U.S. has undertaken and future
joint cooperation in the coming stage.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Richardson hailed the favorable atmosphere of
investment in Egypt and measures taken by the Egyptian government
to encourage the private sector to set up power ventures.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Richardson did not deny that his tour is aiming to
persuade Arab leaders to slash the soaring prices of oil, voicing
hope the prices will be decreased.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. secretary also conveyed a message to Mubarak from U.S.
President Bill Clinton, which appreciates and supports the role
played by Mubarak and Egypt in the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Richardson is currently on a 10-day multi-leg trip that began in
Mexico on February 19. He arrived here Wednesday following a visit
to Israel and the Palestinian self-rule areas. He is going to
Kuwait and Saudi Arabia to continue his tour. 
</P>
</TEXT>
