<DOCNO> XIE20000224.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Launches All-out Effort to Stop TB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization (
WHO) and its partners are making an all-out effort to control the
further spread of tuberculosis (TB) in the Western Pacific Region,
WHO Regional Director Shigeru Omi said Thursday in a press
conference.
</P>
<P>
Omi made the remarks as TB experts and high-level government
officials from the region were holding a meeting in Manila from
Monday to review and finalize a strategic plan to stop TB in the
region.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, which is scheduled to conclude Thursday, will also
identify resource requirement and specify international agencies
to address the problem.
</P>
<P>
According to Omi, almost 30 percent of the global tuberculosis
burden is in the Western Pacific Region and 70 percent of the
patients are in the 15 to 54 age group, the most productive
segment of the population.
</P>
<P>
Omi said the regional notification rate of new infectious cases
per 100,000 population increased steadily from 17 in 1993 to 24 in
1998, prompting the WHO Regional Committee for the Western Pacific
declared 1999 as a year of the TB crisis in the region.
</P>
<P>
Omi noted that the disease poses a serious health problem not
only in developing countries but in newly industrialized and
developed countries as well due to lack of political commitment
and increasing movement of people.
</P>
<P>
He warned that tuberculosis will continue to spread unless
drastic measures are taken now with greater political commitment.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he stressed, the number of TB/HIV co-infection cases,
although still low regionwide, is expected to rise over the next
few years, particularly, if no significant action is taken.
</P>
<P>
WHO aims to reduce TB cases in the Western Pacific Region by
half from 2000 to 2010 through appropriate control measures using
the DOTS (directly observed treatment, short course) strategy.
</P>
<P>
In 1993, WHO declared tuberculosis as a global emergency and,
in 1998, launched the STOP TB initiative to push TB control
further up on the political agenda. However, only limited progress
was made in controlling the disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
