<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Ex-combatants Invade Farms for Land Balance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's ex-combatants in
southern Masvingo Province Wednesday invaded four more farms,
bringing the number of farms invaded over the past week to seven,
the daily Herald reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Masvingo Provincial War Veterans' Association Chairman
Munyaradzi Mhike confirmed the invasions and said the
ex-combatants would invade more farms in the province.
</P>
<P>
Mhike pointed out that the invasions should not be misconstrued
to be a threat to the white farmers.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted that the ex-combatants' action was an
expression of the need to resolve the land imbalance and the
urgent need to have land redistributed.
</P>
<P>
Although he could not give details of the exact number of
ex-combatants involved in the invasion, the Herald is reliably
informed that there are about 400 of them.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said that at least 100 ex-combatants are believed
to have earlier invaded the three unnamed farms.
</P>
<P>
With the rate of invasion already sending chills down the
spines of the white farmers in the vast province, Masvingo
Provincial Governor Josaya Hungwe Wednesday travelled to Harare to
give a "comprehensive report" on the issue to Vice-President
Joseph Msika.
</P>
<P>
With all 1.6 million hectares of land identified for
designation in Masvingo Province contested in court, the
ex-combatants had hoped that a new constitution would provide a
lasting solution to their problems.
</P>
<P>
Their hopes were dashed when the majority of voters rejected
the draft constitution in a national referendum held two weeks
ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
