<HEADLINE> World Bank Funds Water Projects in E. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has set aside
73 billion shillings (some 100 million U.S. dollars) to help
local authorities around Lake Victoria to build sewerage,
sanitation and water supply projects, the Daily Nation reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the Lake Victoria Environment Management Program
said the funds, through the East African Cooperation secretariat
in Arusha, would be used to support projects in Kisumu (Kenya),
Mwanza and Musoma (Tanzania)
</P>
<P>
and Jinja, Port Bell and Entebbe (Uganda).
</P>
<P>
The aim of the funding is to reduce the depositing of harmful
chemical substances and wasters that are already polluting Lake
Victoria and endangering the lake's resources, the officials
said.
</P>
<P>
For decades, the lake has been polluting by local authorities,
resulting in hyacinth invasion among other negative effects on
the resources of the lake.
</P>
<P>
Lake Victoria borders the three east African countries and
covers 68,800 hectares of water mass. The lake abounds in various
species of fish, mainly exported to the European Union.l
</P>
<P>
It produces millions of jobs and annual export earnings to the
tune of about 600 million dollars, representing a revenue base of
between 240 to 270 million dollars per annum for the lakeside
community. 
</P>
</TEXT>
