<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One Killed, 12 Injured In California Prison Riot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, February 23 (Xinhua) -- One inmate was killed and
12 were injured when guards opened fire Wednesday to stop what
officials called a race riot at the Pelican Bay maximum security
prison in northern California.
</P>
<P>
Officials said the riot broke out in two prison yards at 9:30 a.
m. local time when about 200 black and Hispanic prisoners attacked
each other with a variety of crudely fashioned weapons, including
knives. The fighting lasted half an hour.
</P>
<P>
A California Department of Corrections spokesman said that in
addition to those injured by gunfire from the guards, there were "
multiple inmates with stab wounds." The injured were taken to
local hospitals by a fleet of 16 ambulances.
</P>
<P>
Guards opened fire to stop the riot when repeated bursts of
tear gas had failed to stop the melee and when they thought a
prisoner's life was threatened by another prisoner, spokesman
Steve Green said.
</P>
<P>
The riot was fueled by racial disputes between the black and
Hispanic inmates in a recreation yard at the prison that houses
some of the state's most dangerous inmates in northern California.
</P>
<P>
A special state investigative team was flown in from Sacramento
to examine Wednesday's riot, CNN reported.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's death was the first time since May 1997 when an
inmate had been killed during a prison disturbance in California.
</P>
<P>
The prison, which opened in 1989, is situated on 270 acres of
forest land 20 miles on the rugged northern California Coast south
of the Oregon state line.
</P>
<P>
Built for 2,280 inmates, according to local officials, the
facility now houses 3,400. About 1,200 are in permanent lockdown
conditions.
</P>
<P>
Many inmates were sent to Pelican Bay after being involved in
violence at other California prisons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
