<DOCNO> XIE20000224.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Construction of South Korea's 16th Nuclear Reactors Completed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The construction of No. 4
reactor of South Korean Uljin Nuclear Power Plant was completed in
North Kyongsang Province Thursday after seven years and seven
months.
</P>
<P>
The nuclear reactor is the second one built with South Korea's
own technology which brings the number of the country's nuclear
reactors to 16.
</P>
<P>
South Korea now has four nuclear power plants with 16 reactors
with a total capacity of 13.72 million kilowatt. The four plants
are located in Youngkwang, Kuri, Wolsung and Uljin, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The 16 nuclear reactors now account for 29 percent of power
generating facilities and supply over 40 percent of the country's
electric power.
</P>
<P>
Of 14 more nuclear reactors South Korea has decided to build
before the year 2015, four are under construction.
</P>
<P>
"Reactors are the most ideal energy source for a country like
ours that lacks natural resources," said Prime Minister Park Tae-
joon at a ceremony marking the 16th reactor's completion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
