<HEADLINE> Dredging Project at Dianchi Lake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, February 24 (Xinhua) -- China will start the second
stage of dredging the Dianchi Lake, the sixth largest of China's
fresh water lakes.
</P>
<P>
The project, approved by the State Development Planning
Commission, will invest 147 million yuan. Some 2.25 million cubic
meters of silt will be dredged from the bottom of the Lake. The
project is expected to be completed by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
The famous lake, on a high plateau in southwest China's Yunnan
Province covers an area of 307 square kilometers.
</P>
<P>
However, the lake's water has become murky because of
industrial and domestic waste discharged into the Lake over the
past 20 years. Algae is also causing problems.
</P>
<P>
The Yunnan Provincial Environmental Department launched a clean-
up project in March last year. The 250-million-yuan (30 million U.
S. dollars) project has resulted in the removal of 4.2 million
cubic meters of silt on a 2.8-square-kilometer area. The depth of
the lake increased by one meter when the dredging project was
completed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
