<HEADLINE> Zambia Builds up Security Along Border With Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Zambia has deployed troops
along its border with Angola following recent attacks on villages
by suspected Angolan rebel forces, the Post newspaper reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian troops are now in full control of the border areas,
 Information and Broadcasting Minister Newstead Zimba was quoted
as saying Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Zimba, who is also chief government spokesman, said that his
government is taking measures to ensure Zambians living along the
Angolan border are safe.
</P>
<P>
"That area is flooded and the situation is unclear, the army
has been deployed there," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Zambian Defense Minister Chitalu Sampa said that his
country shall not allow the Angolans to fight in Zambia.
</P>
<P>
Sampa told the press that the situation at the Zambian border
with Angola has returned to normal.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Zambian security personnel had been deployed
along the border and that the "bandits" who attacked the Zambian
villages two weeks ago had since deserted the area.
</P>
<P>
Sampa said the appeal by the Angolan government to fight the
National Union for Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) rebels
from the Zambian territory had not been accepted because it would
just escalate war in the region.
</P>
<P>
Some Zambian villagers in Chavuma area have reportedly been
attacked by suspected UNITA rebels, leaving most villagers in fear
while others have fled their homes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
