<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyclone Kills 2, Leaves 250,000 Homeless In Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Cyclone Eline's heavy rains and
strong winds in the eastern and southern districts of Zimbabwe on
Wednesday killed two people, swept away at least eight major
bridges and left some 250,000 people homeless and without food,
the daily Herald reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The tropical storm is sweeping Zimbabwe from neighboring
Mozambique two days ago.
</P>
<P>
There are 130,000 affected families and it is suspected that
hundreds of people will have to be rescued from shrinking islands
of higher ground and trees.
</P>
<P>
Director of the Department of Civil Protection Madzudzo
Pawadyire Wednesday said the government started to use its
strategic grain reserve to help the people in the affected areas.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Local Government and National Housing John Nkomo
said in a statement on Wednesday that there was a big risk of
flooding in the Zambezi Valley in north Zimbabwe owing to the
opening of floodgates at Kariba Dam on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"The combined effects of the water released from Kariba Dam and
the substantial rains this season are likely to increase the risk
of flooding downstream," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
He urged all the communities to move to higher ground before
Saturday until the river subsides to its usual level.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Meteorological Services said the tropical
cyclone had now changed to a tropical depression and had weakened
in intensity.
</P>
<P>
This could result in the amount of rainfall decreasing,
although there are chances that it could still get heavy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
