<DOCNO> XIE20000224.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scores Bring Tension Among Children, Parents, and Teachers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Though the Ministry of
Education has been carrying out regulations to lessen the
schooling burden of students in primary and middle schools in
China, the score-oriented educational system has still made it
hard to win applause from teachers and parents.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Education stipulates that all the primary and
middle schools abolish the usual practice of deciding students'
position in the class only by their scores, and grades are to
become confidential when the new term begins this March.
</P>
<P>
However, score-oriented education in China may make it hard for
quality-oriented and talent-inspired education to go onto the
stage, said officials with the Fuzhou Educational Administration,
south China's Fujian Province.
</P>
<P>
It has been a routine ever since the founding of New China in
1949 that scores is the crucial factor in deciding the students'
enrollment into the high schools and universities.
</P>
<P>
About 35.1 percent of the 950 children and 42.7 percent of the
964 parents under the recent survey in north China's Tianjin agree
that scores, not behavior, nor lack of independence, decide on the
relationships among the two generations.
</P>
<P>
The scores has also been the decisive factor in the
relationships of teachers and students. Teachers in Fuzhou seem to
be always critical to their students, those with low grades in
particular, said the students under the poll.
</P>
<P>
Those children also said they feel suppressed, for neither the
parents nor the teachers seem to care at all about their minds,
the only criterion in judging an outstanding student is his or her
school transcript. There exist no heart-to-heart contact and
exchange of attitudes among students and teachers and parents.
</P>
<P>
A survey among Beijing primary school pupils shows that 46.8
percent admit that they are afraid of some of their teachers, and
52.5 percent said that they feel anxious when they are required to
go to the teachers' office.
</P>
<P>
The uneasy feeling has discouraged the children to speak their
unhappiness and true feelings out to the adults. And anxiety about
scores has even caused some extreme cases.
</P>
<P>
Xu Li, a high school student in east China's Zhejiang Province
beat his mother to death when his mother warned him again and
again that he had to increase his position in his class among the
top ten from the 18th last semester.
</P>
<P>
Officials with the city educational administration point out
that in the older generation's mind, strict requirements and
authority maintenance all the time are the only means to help the
children enter the higher educational institutions and turn into
well-behaved youths.
</P>
<P>
However, parents and teachers can succeed in nurturing the
children into good-mannered ladies and gentlemen only by their own
doings, not by sermons and poker faces, said psychologists.
</P>
<P>
If they want children to say "sorry" to them when the kids do
wrongs, and to say "thank you" to them when they get help from the
adults, the older generation should show the young with their own
conduct. Good school transcripts do not necessarily bring the
adults a good boy or a girl, they noted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000224.0247 </DOCNO>
