<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senior Myanmar Official for Introducing Law on SMEs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, February 24 (Xinhua) -- A high-ranking Myanmar official
Wednesday stressed the need to promote small and medium
enterprises(SMEs) in the country.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening session here of a workshop on AFTA
process and AICO scheme, Brigadier-General Abel, Myanmar minister
at the Office of the Chairman of the State Peace and Development
Council, said that the SMEs have the potential to play a
significant role in the framework of ASEAN Free Trade Area (AFTA),
liberalization of services, ASEAN Industrial Cooperation(AICO)
scheme and the ASEAN Investment Area (AIA).
</P>
<P>
He emphasized the need for his country to promulgate its own
SME policy and law.
</P>
<P>
While admitting that Myanmar's SMEs are not as developed as in
other ASEAN countries, and are not regionally competitive, the
minister pointed out that they can increase the growth of the
country's economy and supplement imports.
</P>
<P>
He also admitted that Myanmar's SMEs, as in other countries,
face many problems such as lack of technology, finance,
information and human resources development, and called for
seeking ways and means to minimize and eliminate these problems.
</P>
<P>
In fiscal year 1998-99, he noted, Myanmar has only 453
enterprises employing more than 100 workers, accounting for 0.8
percent of the total enterprises in the processing and
manufacturing sector.
</P>
<P>
Of these, 0.26 percent is in the private sector, a negligible
number in the cooperative sector and the rest in the public sector.
</P>
<P>
He added that enterprises employing less than ten workers
accounted for almost 95 percent of the sector, of which almost 92
percent are in the private sector.
</P>
<P>
The three-day workshop, which began Wednesday, is sponsored by
the Myanmar Institute of Strategic and International Studies and
Sasakawa Peace Foundation of Japan with the support of National
AFTA Unit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
