<DOCNO> XIE20000224.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> TB Still Taking Heavy Toll in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Nepal has some 80,000 TB (
Tuberculosis) patients and 8,000 to 11,000 of them die every year,
according to Dirgha Singh Bam, Director of the National
Tuberculosis Center.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a three-day world conference on TB that began
Wednesday, Bam said that TB is still a major health problem in the
world, especially in the developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Poverty and TB coexist in a vicious circle, as poor individuals,
poor communities and poor countries have the highest rates of TB
that impoverishes those with the disease, according to experts who
presented their working papers at the conference.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics, about three million cases of TB occur
each year in the South Asia countries, representing 40 percent of
cases worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Closely followed DOTS (Direct Observation Treatment Short
Course) will go a long way toward putting a lid over the growing
number of TB patients, said the experts at the conference.
</P>
<P>
Since Nepal adopted DOTS strategy in 1996, 55 percent of the
total population has been covered and the cure rate is more than
85 percent,which is very encouraging experience, according to Bam.
</P>
<P>
About 120 representatives from 18 countries worldwide are
participating in the conference, which aims to raise awareness
about TB control and to empower individuals and organizations with
skills, motivation and knowledge to control the disease.
</P>
<P>
The conference is organized by TB. Net, a three-year old global
TB network based in Nepal which maintains an Internet resource
center for TB control. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000224.0252 </DOCNO>
