<HEADLINE> New Zealand PM Meets China's NPC Vice-Chairman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, February 24 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Prime Minister
Helen Clark met here Thursday with visiting Vice-Chairman of China
's National People's Congress (NPC) Standing Committee Zhou
Guangzhao and the NPC delegation headed by him.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Zhou conveyed Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji's
cordial regards to Prime Minister Helen Clark and expressed the
hope that Ms Clark would visit China again at a time convenient to
her.
</P>
<P>
Helen Clark, who visited China in 1997 in the capacity of
opposition leader, recalled her meeting with Premier Zhu during
the trip. She asked Vice-Chairman Zhou to convey her best wishes
to Premier Zhu and said she would like to visit China again.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of Sino-New Zealand relations, Zhou noted that New
Zealand was one of the earliest west countries to recognize the
People's Republic of China. The diplomatic ties between China and
New Zealand, he said, were established as early as 70s when the
New Zealand Labor Party was in power.
</P>
<P>
He highly appreciated the development of friendly relations and
exchanges between the two countries and between the two
parliaments in particular in the past decades, and hoped to see
the relations steadily growing in the new century.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Clark noted that Chinese President Jiang Zemin's
visit to New Zealand last September was very successful. She said
she was very glad to have a meeting with President Jiang during
his visit.
</P>
<P>
She said the new government with the New Zealand Labor Party as
its main ruling party values relations with China and will work
for closer New Zealand-China ties.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Vice-Chairman Zhou had separate meetings with New
Zealand Minister of Foreign Affairs and Trade Phil Goff; Minister
of Research, Science and Technology Pete Hodgson; and Opposition
Leader Jenny Shipley. He and his delegation attended a
parliamentary luncheon hosted by Jonathan Hunt, speaker of the New
Zealand Parliament.
</P>
<P>
The NPC delegation is scheduled to leave here for Auckland, the
biggest city in the country, before leaving for home on Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
