<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Trade Position Better in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, February 24 (Xinhua) -- An unexpected slump in
imports brought New Zealand's trade position unexpectedly into
balance in January, according to preliminary figures released here
Thursday by Statistics New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
Imports in January were 1.78 billion NZ dollars (872.1 million
U.S. dollars), well down from 3.15 billion NZ dollars (1.54
billion U.S. dollars) in December.
</P>
<P>
Matching that were estimated exports of 1.78 billion NZ dollars
(872.1 million U.S. dollars), down from 2.05 billion NZ dollars (
one billion U.S. dollars) in December.
</P>
<P>
It is a good news for New Zealand's current account deficit
which has been projected by the Treasury and Finance Department
and the Reserve Bank to blow out to around 7.5-8.0 percent of GDP
in March, a level considered horrendous and unsustainable by
economists.
</P>
<P>
Just after release of the figures, the New Zealand dollar
firmed to 48.94 cents of the U.S. dollar while it opened at 48.59
cents of the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
The official statistical department was unable to say whether
the drop in January's imports was sustainable.
</P>
<P>
It said it will release a more definite figure for exports on
March 9th. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
