<DOCNO> XIE20000224.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Officials Welcome Enactment of Bourses Merger Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong Financial
Secretary Donald Tsang welcomed the enactment of the Exchanges and
Clearing Houses (Merger) Bill by the Legislative Council Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Tsang said that it is an essential step for the proposed merger
of the exchanges and the clearing houses, which is an integral
part of the market structure reform announced in the budget speech
last year.
</P>
<P>
"I am pleased to see that the merger proposal has received
support from all quarters, including members of the two exchanges,
the financial market, legislators and the public at large," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"The next step will be the implementation of the merger
scheduled to take place on March 6. The international financial
community has been watching this swift development with envy. I am
glad that Hong Kong has once again demonstrated our ability to
respond quickly to competition and challenges," Tsang added.
</P>
<P>
Under the bill, a new holding company, known as the Hong Kong
Exchanges and Clearing Limited (HKEC), will be set up as a result
of the planned demutualization and merger of Hong Kong's stock
exchange, futures exchange and clearing houses.
</P>
<P>
HKEC will be a public listed company owned by private investors
and the government, but the government's role would be minimal.
</P>
<P>
The aim of the market reform is to enhance the Hong Kong stock
market's competitiveness to meet the challenge of an increasingly
globalized market place driven by advancement of technology and
the emergence of a growing population of sophisticated investors,
Hong Kong officials said.
</P>
<P>
The merger is expected to increase transparency and efficiency,
open up the field to more players and ultimately attract more
companies to list in Hong Kong, officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
