<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Development Forum to Be Held in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Governance, institutional reform,
infrastructure development and corruption will be the major issues
for discussion in the next "Bangladesh Development Forum" meeting
to be held in Paris in April, Bangladeshi newspapers reported
Thursday quoting a World Bank official.
</P>
<P>
World Bank Country Director Fredrik Thomas Temple said the
Forum meeting, scheduled for April 13 and 14, will on the first
day discuss Bangladesh's strategies for poverty reduction and
institutional reform. On the second day, the meeting will focus on
the infrastructural constraints and problems in project
implementation.
</P>
<P>
Unlike the previous years, there will be no pledges on future
aid from the donors who will provide aid to the government after
reviewing the proposed projects and the implementation rate of the
previous ones, Temple noted.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank official said a pre-Forum meeting will be held
in Dhaka on March 28, where the representatives of civic society
will expound their views on the country's problems and prospect.
</P>
<P>
Like the previous years, the Bangladeshi government will
present a country memorandum at the meeting, highlighting the
efforts for reducing poverty, establishing good governance and
reforming financial and social sectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
