<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Korean Ruling Coalition Breaks Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean ruling
coalition was dissolved Thursday morning as the United Liberal
Democrats (ULD) declared an end of partnership with the ruling
Millennium Democratic Party (MDP).
</P>
<P>
"We have decided to completely give up the road to the ruling
coalition and be newly born," said ULD President Lee Han-dong at a
press conference attended by ULD founder and honorary chairman Kim
Jong-pil.
</P>
<P>
The declaration demonstrated an end to a ruling coalition
government system that was made by an agreement between President
Kim Dae-jung and Kim Jong-pil before the 1997 presidential
election.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the two Kims agreed to change the nation's
constitution by 1999 to create a parliamentary cabinet system.
</P>
<P>
"It was the common goal of the coalition government and a
promise to the people to open a new era of hope through the grand
reconciliation of industrial and democratic forces. But the
promise was completely broken," said the ULD president.
</P>
<P>
ULD cabinet members, including Prime Minister Park Tae-joon,
will individually decide whether to resign or stay in the ULD, Lee
said.
</P>
<P>
In a response to the breakup, the South Korean presidential
office expressed deep regret over the ULD's declaration.
</P>
<P>
"We expect the ULD to maintain the spirit of cooperation in
state affairs as one of two axis that have realized the power
shift and the overcoming of the economic crisis," Presidential
spokesman Park Joon-young said.
</P>
<P>
The breakup came after non-governmental groups put ULD honorary
chairman Kim Jong-pil on a unqualified-politician list for the
elections.
</P>
<P>
The ULD has repeatedly attacked its coalition partner MDP,
saying that the latter is abetting the non-governmental groups'
smear campaign against the ULD leader.
</P>
<P>
The breakup is believed to turn the parliamentary elections
into a battle between the ruling MDP and three opposition parties -
- the Grand National Party GNP, the ULD, and a GNP splinter, which
has not been named after it dropped out from the GNP last Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
