<HEADLINE> Indian Government Postpones Petro Price Hike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government
deferred on Wednesday night a proposed hike in the prices of
petroleum products across the country till the middle of next
month due to pressure from its allies, local media reported on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The proposed price hike for products like diesel, kerosene and
cooking gas, which was expected to be announced in the parliament
on Thursday, has been deferred by more than two weeks, the Times
of India quoted government sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Indian government has suggested the price hike as a measure
to save subsidies on petroleum products, which are surging rapidly
due to the rising crude oil prices in the international market.
</P>
<P>
However, the ruling Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP), or Indian
People's Party, met a strong opposition from some of its allied
parties on this issue, local media said.
</P>
<P>
Those against the price hike argued that such a step would
severely hit the ordinary people and have a cascading effect on
the prices of items of daily use.
</P>
<P>
They also suggested the government mobilize alternative
resources to prevent an immediate hike in petroleum prices, said
the Times of India.
</P>
<P>
Following a meeting of the ruling alliance on Wednesday, the
government changed its mind and decided to postpone the price hike.
</P>
<P>
The Times of India quoted a senior government official as
saying that the ruling coalition should remain united in the face
of attempts by the Congress and other opposition parties to put
the government on the mat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
