<DOCNO> XIE20000224.0275 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Sees Strong Recovery in 1999: MTI </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Singapore economy enjoyed a
strong and firm economic recovery in 1999 and is expected to
maintain the growth momentum in 2000, Ministry of Trade and
Industry (MTI)said in its 1999 national economic survey released
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Singapore economic output expanded by 5.4 percent in 1999,
after an anemic 0.4 percent growth in 1999, with all major sectors
except the construction and business services improving in the
year compared to a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The growth was largely led by the 6.7 percent expansion in
external demand and propped mainly by growth in manufacturing,
transport &AMP; communications, wholesale &AMP; retail trade sectors.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, manufacturing sector, riding on the strength of the
global electronics demand and the regional recover, staged a
strong turnaround to grow by 14 percent. The whole sale &AMP; retail
trade sector reversed the 4.1 percent decline in 1998 to see a 7.1
percent recovery and the transport &AMP; communications sector also
enjoyed a 7.1 percent growth on the back of the 5.5 percent growth
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The hotels &AMP; restaurants sector expanded by 3.7 percent last
year helped by the recovery in visitor arrivals and improving
consumer sentiments while the financial services sector registered
flat growth in 1999 following a 8.1 percent fall in 1998.
</P>
<P>
However, the construction sector suffered from a 12 percent
contraction in 1999 in a sharp contrast with the 4.4 percent
growth in 1998 while the business services sector edged up
marginally by 0.1 percent, sharply slower than the 5.1 percent
growth in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The other economic indicators also testified to a good
performance in Singapore's economy in 1999, with total investment
commitments in manufacturing sector reaching 80 billion Singapore
dollars (about 4.8 billion U.S. dollars) and total business
spending commitments in the services sector hitting 1.6 billion
Singapore dollars (about 952 million U.S. dollars), total external
trade rebounding by 8.1 percent,new job gains totaling 41,900 in
the labor market, labor productivity growth rebounding by 5.8
percent while business cost index falling 12 percent in the
manufacturing sector and 3.9 percent in the services sector.
</P>
<P>
The MTI said the outlook for the Singapore economy is bright in
view of the favorable external environment, citing the return to
normality of the global economic conditions, the continued strong
growth in the U.S. economy and the firming in the EU economic
growth, the gradual recovery of the Japanese economy and the sharp
rebound in the crisis-hit countries as well as strong global
electronic demand and the revival in intra-regional trade.
</P>
<P>
It also noted a number of risks to the global economy,
including the fragile recovery in the Japanese economy, the
stronger specter of inflation, the economic slowdown in the U.S.
and the moderation in the economic recovery of Asian economies.
</P>
<P>
Taking into account all these factors, the MTI said it
maintains its 2000 GDP forecast of 4.5 -6.5 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
