<DOCNO> XIE20000224.0276 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Calls for Promoting Regional SMEs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, February 24 (Xinhua) -- A high-ranking Myanmar official
Wednesday called for promoting small and medium enterprises (SMEs)
in Southeast Asian countries to develop the private sector.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening session here of a workshop on ASEAN Free
Trade Area (AFTA) process and ASEAN Industrial Cooperation (AICO)
scheme, Brigadier-General Abel, Myanmar minister at the Office of
the Chairman of the State Peace and Development Council, said the
success of AFTA depends on the private sector, adding that without
the active participation of the sector, ASEAN Vision 2020 cannot
materialize.
</P>
<P>
He noted that ASEAN's private sector, including SMEs, account
for more than 90 percent of the manufacturing sector.
</P>
<P>
The minister stressed the need for expanding area of
cooperation in the AICO projects, saying that new ASEAN member
countries should be given opportunities in the scheme.
</P>
<P>
Up to December 1999, there were 74 AICO projects reportedly
participated by the original five ASEAN member countries not
including Brunei.
</P>
<P>
The AICO, initiated in the past by ASEAN, was newly phased in
1995 with the agreement of the ASEAN member countries to make it
more effective in bringing ASEAN industrial development and
cooperation to a higher plane.
</P>
<P>
The AICO scheme, based on the principles and concepts of the
Common Effective Preferential Tariff (CEPT) scheme for the AFTA,
minimizes tariff dissimilarities and offers qualified
participating companies the immediate benefit of the CEPT tariff
rates in the range of zero to five percent.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the Bold Measures, adopted by ASEAN leaders
to provide special incentive and privileges to attract foreign
direct investment into the region for a two-year action program,
the ASEAN member countries agreed to waive the 30 percent national
equity requirement under the AICO scheme in 1999-2000.
</P>
<P>
The three-day workshop, which began Wednesday, is sponsored by
the Myanmar Institute of Strategic and International Peace
Foundation of Japan with the support of the National AFTA Unit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
