<HEADLINE> Italian President Calls for Anti-Racism Charter for Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, February 23 (Xinhua) -- Europe should introduce a binding
common charter within this year to drive the ghost of racism out
of the continent by force of law, Italian President Carlo Azeglio
Ciampi said in Trieste, Italy, on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Racism can never be tolerated inside the European Union (EU),
which is not just an economic and political body but above all, an
upholder of common values, Ciampi said.
</P>
<P>
In this sense, he said that the charter enshrining liberty,
democracy and respect for all human races should become the
foundation of a future European constitution.
</P>
<P>
Noting that racial hatred has left Europe with a bloody mark in
history, he asked people never to forget that and to ensure
tragedies will never be repeated.
</P>
<P>
Ciampi will visit the San Sabba rice farm near Trieste, the
site of Italy's only Nazi death camp built by German fascists
where over 5000 Jewish victims were killed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
