<HEADLINE> Poland's Central Bank Raises Lending Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, February 23 (Xinhua) -- Poland's central bank on
Wednesday decided to raise the interest rates of three kinds of
businesses by one percentage point respectively starting on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
This is the second interest rate hike in less than four months
in order to contain inflation, curb loans and boost bank savings.
</P>
<P>
The Polish monetary policy committee announced Wednesday that
the bank's discount rate will be lifted from 19 percent to 20
percent, lombard rate from 20.5 to 21.5 and intervention rate from
16.5 to 17.5.
</P>
<P>
Economists here hold that the worsened economic indexes in
January have triggered the rate hike.
</P>
<P>
Last November, the central bank raised its basic lending rates
by 2.5-3.5 percentage points. However, the long-time slack economy
continued to deteriorate, leading to a current account deficit
exceeding 1 billion U.S. dollars in January as against 11.7
billion dollars for the whole year of 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
