<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU, Mexico to Sign Free Trade Deal Next Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VILAMOURA, Portugal, February 23 (Xinhua) -- The European
Union (EU) and Mexico have agreed to sign a free trade deal next
month, officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The deal will be signed during a special EU summit in Lisbon on
March 23-24 and is expected to be implemented on June 1 this year.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached after talks between negotiators from
both sides in the southern Portuguese resort town of Vilamoura.
</P>
<P>
Under the free trade deal, tariffs will be removed on 95
percent of two-way trade by the year 2007.
</P>
<P>
Portuguese Foreign Minister Jaime Gama, whose country holds the
EU's rotating presidency, said he was convinced that the European
Parliament would approve the deal so that it could come into force
as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
Mexican Foreign Minister Rosario Green said her government is
trying to persuade the Senate to ratify the deal before the
proposed signing date.
</P>
<P>
Portuguese media, which described the agreement as the "most
ambitious deal" ever signed by the EU with a single country
outside the bloc, said the deal was based on mutual political and
economic interests.
</P>
<P>
With the trade deal, EU could increase its influence in Latin
America and put itself in a better position to compete with the
United States and Canada with which Mexico will implement the
North American Free Trade Agreement in 2003.
</P>
<P>
Officials said the EU will also begin talks in April with the
southern American trade bloc Mercosur, which groups Argentina,
Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay, with Chile and Bolivia as associate
members.
</P>
<P>
Recently, the EU has concluded a free trade deal with South
Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000224.0288 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chongqing Pledges to Play Bigger Role in Western Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Chongqing, the largest city
in southwest China, has drawn up a series of measures to pave the
way for the surge of economic development planned for the country'
s vast western region.
</P>
<P>
A municipal office in charge of economic development in western
China was recently set up to carry out this work.
</P>
<P>
Bao Shuding, mayor of Chongqing, said in a government work
report to the municipal people's congress that the city would
invest 240 billion yuan in 107 key infrastructure projects in the
next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
At present, 50 projects are underway covering the fields of
transport, environmental protection at the Three Gorges Dam
Project, harbor construction and information. Work on the
remaining 57 will start either this year or next.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing plans to build a high-tech system with information,
bioengineering, environmental protection and optical-electric
integration as its pillars in the coming decade.
</P>
<P>
Lei Hengshun, director of Southwest China Development Research
Institute of Chongqing University, said Chongqing is in a unique
position to aid western expansion: It ranks first among 10
provinces and autonomous regions in western China in both tertiary
trade development and direct foreign investment usage, and second
in per capita gross domestic product, and it has formed an
economic zone among Chengdu, Chongqing and Yibin City.
</P>
<P>
Yu Ronggen, president of the Chongqing Academy of Social
Sciences, said development of western China offers a golden
opportunity for Chongqing to solve its four toughest issues:
invigoration of state industrial enterprises, resettlement of dam
area residents, improvement of poor people's living standards and
ecological construction.
</P>
<P>
The first international conference on the development of
western China will be held here in June.  
</P>
</TEXT>
