<HEADLINE> Northeast China's Dalian Striving to Boost Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Dalian, a port city of
northeast China's Liaoning Province, has been making pains-taking
efforts to boost tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, the city has dispatched 12 tourism
promotion missions to Japan, the Republic of Korea (ROK), Hong
Kong, Russia and Southeast Asian countries and has established
friendly cooperation ties with more than 20 overseas tourism
organizations since 1999.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, local tourism organizations in the city have
managed to offer 16 tour programs with special features including
shopping, golf-playing and seafood tasting.
</P>
<P>
The city has invested heavily in rebuilding the roads, growing
more trees and turfs to bring the city's greenery cover to 40
percent, constructing 20 new plazas and erecting 172 sculptures of
different kinds along the streets, and building scenic sites at
more than 160 places.
</P>
<P>
A total of 20.26 million people visited Dalian last year,
including 261,000 overseas tourists, up 30 percent from 1998, said
the local sources.
</P>
<P>
Tourism industry generated 7.4 billion yuan (892 million U.S.
dollars) in total earnings in 1999, up 20 percent from 1998, and
made up 7.4 percent of the city's gross domestic product (GDP).
</P>
</TEXT>
