<HEADLINE> Price Cuts Bring Spending Surge in Telecom Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 24 (Xinhua) -- China's telecommunications
sector witnessed an increase of 38.7 billion yuan (4.7 billion U.S.
dollars) in consumer spending last year after the government cut
certain fees twice.
</P>
<P>
The latest figures from the State Development Planning
Commission(SDPC) show that the average initial charge for
telephone installment has dropped from 1,010 yuan to 690 yuan,
falling 31.7 percent, and the average registration fee for mobile
phones has decreased from 800 yuan to 500 yuan, plummeting 37.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
Before the reduction of fees, new users of telephones in China
grew at an average monthly pace of 2.4 million, while the amount
soared to 3.7 million after the reduction.
</P>
<P>
An official in the price regulation department of the SDPC said
further fee reductions might help with the expansion of the
telecommunications market and the stimulation of domestic demand.
Adjustment of telecom fees in rural areas is also underway, he
added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
