<DOCNO> XIE20000224.0292 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> INTERFET Withdraws From East </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations-sanctioned
International Forces for East Timor (INTERFET) ended a five-month
peacekeeping operation on Wednesday and handed over to U.N.
peacekeepers, according to reports reaching here from Dili,
capital of East Timor, on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
INTERFET commander Major General Peter Cosgrove took the salute
at a low-key farewell ceremony outside his temporary headquarters.
He said the force had been lucky to have achieved its task with
relatively little violence.
</P>
<P>
Cosgrove sailed out of Dili harbor around midday, shortly after
the INTERFET's flag was lowered for the last time.
</P>
<P>
The 19-nation force, sanctioned by the U.N. Security Council,
landed in East Timor on September 20 last year after pro-Indonesia
militias went on a spree of violence and destruction.
</P>
<P>
At least 300 people are known to have been killed and thousands
of buildings burned or damaged, before INTERFET troops restored
order.
</P>
<P>
INTERFET has been replaced by a 23-nation United Nations
peacekeeping force led by Lieutenant General Jaime de los Santos
of the Philippines, although 80 percent of the U.N. force of
around 9,000 troops will transfer from INTERFET.
</P>
<P>
East Timor was a Portuguese colony for more than 400 years. On
August 30 last year, more than 400,000 East Timorese took part in
a U.N.-sponsored ballot and overwhelmingly voted for independence.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. expects to administer the former Portuguese colony for
two to three years leading to independence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
