<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Armed Group Members Surrender to Myanmar Govt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Seventeen members of the Lahu
anti-government ethnic armed group operating in Myanmar's Shan
state surrendered to the government Monday, official newspaper The
New Light of Myanmar reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Lahu armed group members, who "exchanged arms for peace"
with the government forces in the Triangle Region Command area,
was led by their company commander U Saw La Mon.
</P>
<P>
Last month, a total of 72 members of the Shan-State United
Revolutionary Army, another anti-government Shan ethnic armed
group operating in the state, also surrendered to the government,
according to earlier official report.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, a total of 17 anti-government ethnic armed groups as
well as the Mong Tai Army, led by former drug warlord Khun Sa,
have made peace with the government with cease-fire agreements
reached between them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
