<DOCNO> XIE20000224.0295 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macedonian Army on Alert at Border With Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, February 23 (Xinhua) -- Macedonia has put its army on
alert at the border with Kosovo in response to increasing tensions
in the neighboring Yugoslav province, according to reports from
the Macedonian capital Skopje.
</P>
<P>
A Macedonian Defense Ministry spokesman said his government is
closely following the developments in Kosovo, where the situation
might well get out of control.
</P>
<P>
Recently, the Macedonian Army at the Kosovo border has
increased its numbers and length of patrols to strengthen
inspection in the border area, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the Macedonian Army deployed in Kumanovo near the
Kosovo border has raised its degree of combat readiness.
</P>
<P>
In Kosovo, tensions have intensified over the past three weeks
due to Serb-Albanian confrontations in the ethnically divided town
of Mitrovica in the north. The city has been the scene of clashes
between ethnic Albanians and KFOR peacekeepers and armed violence
between hostile Serb and Albanian communities.
</P>
<P>
The unrest in Mitrovica has left nine people dead and about 20
wounded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000224.0296 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Denmark Discovers Richer Natural Gas Reservation in North Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, February 23 (Xinhua) -- Danish energy business
estimates that over 100 billion cubic meters of natural gas are
still buried under the continental shelf in the Danish North Sea
area, far more than previous estimates, the Danish newspaper
Politiken reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Half a year ago, the Danish Oil and Natural Gas Incorporation (
DONG) and Danish Underground Development Group estimated the
Danish North Sea to contain a natural gas reservation of about 70
billion cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
After some re-calculations, however, the two companies now
revised their estimates, saying the reservation under the Danish
North Sea continental shelf remains about 100 billion cubic meters,
almost 50 percent above the previous figure.
</P>
<P>
The new finding means that Denmark will continue to increase
its natural gas production for many years and will have to export
the product to foreign countries due to a saturated domestic
market.
</P>
<P>
For this, Denmark is poised to speed up the construction of
natural gas pipelines in the Baltic Sea to facilitate the export
to Poland. DONG's Vice President Povl Asserhoej said that the
construction, at a cost of about 2.5 billion Denmark kroner (about
338 million U.S. dollars), will hopefully be finished within three
to four years.
</P>
<P>
Denmark began tapping natural gas in the North Sea 30 years ago
when the estimated reservations were about 160 billion cubic
meters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
