<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Anti-drug Official Visits Colombia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, February 23 (Xinhua) -- U.S. anti-drug
official Barry McCaffrey said Wednesday he is visiting Colombia to
evaluate the implementation of Plan Colombia, a government program
against drug trafficking and illegal cultivation.
</P>
<P>
McCaffrey, director of U.S. Drug Enforcement Agency said this
at a press conference immediately following his meeting with
Colombian President Andres Pastrana.
</P>
<P>
Plan Colombia is a multi-billion program designed to fight
narcotics and substitute drug plants such as coca and poppy.
</P>
<P>
McCaffrey said the U.S. concentrates its efforts on
socioeconomic solutions in Colombia, Peru and Bolivia, main
sources of illegal drugs in South America.
</P>
<P>
While expressing appreciation over results in illegal
cultivation eradication in recent years in Peru and Bolivia,
McCaffrey admitted that the situation is different in Colombia
where 25,000 armed men are involved in drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
The plan implementation will require 7.5 billion U.S. dollars,
of which, the United States has promised to provide 1.6 billion
dollars, European and Asian countries, 1.9 billion dollars while
Colombia, 4 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
McCaffrey, who arrived here on Tuesday night, is scheduled to
travel Thursday to Tres Esquinas, Caqueta department, on an
inspection tour of a military base used in drug-fighting
operations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
