<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Plan to Stop Plowing of Farmland in West China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, February 24 (Xinhua)-- Lanzhou, the capital of
northwest China's Gansu Province, plans to stop plowing 66,000
hectares of farmland in the next five years as part of its
ambitious environmental improvement program.
</P>
<P>
According to official sources, 126,000 ha of forest and
grassland will cover the barren mountains by the end of 2009,
increasing Lanzhou's forest acreage to 19 percent and curbing soil
erosion.
</P>
<P>
The 192,000-hectare-forestry program is estimated to cost
nearly 1.9 billion yuan (228 million U.S. dollars). Funds will
come mainly from the government as well as funds raised by local
residents.
</P>
<P>
Local residents are encouraged to take an active part in the
forestation program.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
