<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Homeland Appeals to Students Overseas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Majority of Chinese students
studying abroad have decided to come back home choosing Beijing as
their ideal city to work in, a survey shows.
</P>
<P>
A six-month survey conducted by a research team from the
Science and Technology Commission of Beijing indicates that eight
out of 10 overseas students are willing to return to start their
undertakings after they graduate.
</P>
<P>
Over 60 percent of them choose Beijing as their base, while 19
percent do not plan to come back, according to the survey which
was based on interviews with more than 1,000 Chinese students
studying at universities in the United States, China Daily
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Among those willing to return, 21 percent will do so within
five years, 36 percent within five to 10 years and the others
after 10 years or more.
</P>
<P>
Half of the students planning to come back believe they should
come back to work for their country.
</P>
<P>
The survey also showed that a desire for family reunions
motivated 45 percent of the overseas students to return, and 31
percent believe that their U.S. educational background will mean
more chances to get good jobs when they come back.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
