<DOCNO> XIE20000224.0316 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Waiting for WTO Ruling on U.S. Tax Plan Concerning Export Subsidy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) is
waiting for a ruling by the World Trade Organization (WTO)
Thursday on the legality of a U.S. tax plan which has been found
to constitute a prohibited export subsidy under certain WTO
agreement.
</P>
<P>
A WTO dispute panel report issued last October provides that
the U.S. will have until October 1, 2000, to withdraw the Foreign
Sales Corporations (FSC) scheme because the U.S. scheme is
designed for American corporations to set up companies in a tax
haven as a vehicle of U.S. exports and in this way exempt
substantial amount of due taxes.
</P>
<P>
The European Union filed the case against the United States
over the FSC scheme under the WTO Dispute Settlement Understanding
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Several rounds of consultations were held between the EU and
the U.S. on December 1997, February 1998 and April 1998. However,
the talks failed to reach any agreement.
</P>
<P>
After the WTO panel released the report in the EU's favor in
October last year, the U.S. filed a Notice of Appeal to the WTO
dispute settlement body on November 26.
</P>
<P>
According to the WTO's legal procedure, the report of the WTO's
Appellate Body is expected on February 24, 2000.
</P>
<P>
The EU believes that the FSC scheme exempts U.S. companies from
taxes that would otherwise have to be paid on their export sales.
This constitutes a subsidy on U.S. exports.
</P>
<P>
The WTO Subsidies Agreement establishes that subsidies that are
contingent on export performance are in themselves illegal and
must be immediately withdrawn as they are the most trade
distorting and harmful type of subsidies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
