<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cross-Border Killing of Elephants Uncovered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Police in southwest China's
Yunnan Province and Laos joined hands recently to uncover a cross-
border case of elephant killing.
</P>
<P>
Investigations show that three Laotians went to the Shangyong
Preserve in Xishuangbanna in Yunnan Province early last year, and
killed three wild Asian elephants there. They then took off with a
pair of elephant tusks.
</P>
<P>
The gang confessed that as they were cutting off an elephant
tusk on March 2 last year in the Shangyong Preserve, a Chinese
patrol team appeared and they fled.
</P>
<P>
The dead bodies of two other elephants, a male and a female,
were found by a forest ranger in Shangyong Preserve on May 21 last
year.
</P>
<P>
Upon hearing the report, police in Xishuangbanna conducted a
two-month investigation and concluded that the suspects had come
from Laos, and they asked for the help of their counterparts in
Laos, after which the arrests were made.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
