<DOCNO> XIE20000224.0334 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Football Legend Matthews Dies  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 23 (Xinhua) -- Stanley Matthews, the first
knight of English football, has died aged 85.
</P>
<P>
The former Blackpool and Stoke winger died after a short
illness at North Staffordshire Nuffield hospital.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the private hospital in Newcastle under Lyme
said: "Sir Stanley Matthews died peacefully this evening after a
short illness related to health problems that had first seriously
affected him three years ago."
</P>
<P>
Former England manager Bobby Robson paid tribute to his friend
before England's match with Argentina.
</P>
<P>
"He was one of the greatest players the game has ever seen,"
Robson said. "He ranks alongside players like Pele, Maradona and
Cruyff - and he was one of ours.
</P>
<P>
"He was a lovely fellow and a great friend of mine. It's a
tremendous blow on a nostalgic evening."
</P>
<P>
"He had immense skill - great skill off the ball, a beautiful
dribbler. I'm very sad at the news."
</P>
<P>
The crowd at the start of the England vs Argentina friendly in
Wembley observed a minute's silence in memory of Matthews, whose
death was announced shortly before the match. English players paid
tribute by wearing black arm bands. Matthews was the first
Englishman to be named European Footballer of the Year, a feat he
achieved twice.
</P>
<P>
He scored his only international hat-trick in England's 1937 5-
4 win over Czechoslovakia but the highlight of his long career
came in the 1953 FA Cup Final, which will always be remembered as
"the Matthews Final".
</P>
<P>
During a remarkable 33-year career he won 54 England caps - and
played in another 30 wartime internationals - and he remains the
only man to have played in the old First Division as a 50-year-old.
</P>
<P>
Matthews' funeral will be arranged by Stoke City football club
and his distraught family, the club said.
</P>
<P>
A club spokesman said the former player had been devastated by
the death of his wife last year but often visited the ground to
sign autographs.
</P>
<P>
"He was a massive ambassador for Stoke City football club and
he will be sadly missed by supporters, staff and our players and
indeed footballers worldwide," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Everyone at the club is truly gobsmacked and devastated," he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000224.0335 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kafelnikov Moves into Second Round at London Tennis  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 23 (Xinhua) -- Top seed Yevgeny Kafelnikov of
Russia advanced into the second round of the London indoor tennis
tournament with a straight victory over Andrei Mdevedev on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Kafelnikov, champion in 1988, did just enough to beat his
friend 6-3, 6-4. His baseline play was altogether too consistent
for the French Open runner-up from Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, third seed and world number 11 Tim Henman of Britain
slumped in the first round to Argentine baseliner Mariano Zabaleta.
</P>
<P>
Henman, a finalist in Rotterdam last week, was a shadow of that
player in his 7-6, 7-5 first round defeat at the London Arena.
</P>
<P>
Henman started in fine form and overpowered Zabaleta with some
accurate serving and solid volleys. After losing the first point
of the match on his serve he won the next 18 to take command of
the set.
</P>
<P>
But Zabaleta hung on and as the match wore on Henman began to
wilt. He failed to convert two set points at 5-4 and tell-tale
cracks began to appear in his brittle forehand.
</P>
<P>
The Argentine, who beat Henman in their only previous encounter
on clay in Hamburg last year, grew in confidence and sealed the
tie-break with some classic counter-punching.
</P>
<P>
Henman was well and truly on the ropes in the second set and
was lured into playing at the Argentine's pace and on his terms.
Henman wasted two more break points at 5-5 as Zabaleta briefly
wavered. The Argentine was soon back on track, though, and pounced
on his opponent's serve in the next game.
</P>
<P>
Two sloppy errors and a double fault gave Zabaleta two match
points. Henman saved the first with an ace but moments later he
floated a forehand long to hand his opponent the match.
</P>
<P>
The result was Henman's second consecutive first round exit at
the tournament. In 1999, he was beaten by Slovak Jan Kroslak.
</P>
<P>
Henman was joined at the exit by eighth seed Hicham Arazi who
fell 6-4, 6-3 to Frenchman Fabrice Santoro in a bad-tempered
affair.
</P>
<P>
The Moroccan never settled and eventually received a warning
from the umpire for unsportsmanlike conduct after a series of
verbal outbursts, racket and ball abuse.
</P>
<P>
Sixth seed Cedric Pioline -- conqueror of Henman in the
Rotterdam final last Sunday -- advanced with a 7-5, 7-6 first
round win over Alberto Martin.
</P>
<P>
The French world number 10 was not troubled by the Spaniard and
set up a second round against American Jeff Tarango who beat Swede
Jonas Bjorkman 7-5, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
Tarango was a late replacement for British wildcard Jamie
Delgado who withdrew with a wrist injury. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
