<HEADLINE> Ireland Beats Czechs in Soccer Friendly  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 23 (Xinhua) -- Robbie Keane scored a decisive
goal three minutes from time to give Ireland a 3-2 win over Czech
Republic in a soccer friendly in Dublin on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Keane pounced on a loose ball to fire the winner against the
highly rated Czechs, who won all 10 of their qualifiers en route
to the European championship finals.
</P>
<P>
Striker Jan Koller scored both goals for the Czechs, who led
twice in the first half and are ranked number two in the world
behind Brazil.
</P>
<P>
Anderlecht's Koller stabbed home from close range in the fourth
minute and got his second in the 35th minute when he headed in a
Karel Poborsky cross.
</P>
<P>
Ireland, who missed out on Euro 2000 qualification after a play-
off, had levelled after 16 minutes, with a goal initially credited
to Niall Quinn.
</P>
<P>
But the decisive touch appeared to come off Czech defender
Karel Rada as the two men contested a Mark Kennedy cross.
</P>
<P>
There was an element of good fortune about the second Irish
equaliser two minutes before halftime. Goalkeeper Ladislav Maier
collided with Rada as he went for a cross, leaving defender Ian
Harte to roll the ball into an empty net. 
</P>
