<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Top Executive Body Meets on Kaduna Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 23 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's Federal Executive
Council Wednesday convened an emergency meeting in Abuja,
condemning the riot in the country's northern Kaduna city, which
had reportedly killed 50 people.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after the meeting, Nigerian Information Minister Dapo
Sarumi urged Nigerians, the bar association and the Christian
associations to initiate legal challenge to the controversial
religious code's implementation in the country, which is secular
by constitution.
</P>
<P>
He was quoted by reports reaching here as saying that "it will
not be politically wise for the executive arm to initiate such a
process because it would be accused of bias."
</P>
<P>
According to Sarumi, the federal government sent troops to
Kaduna after it was discovered that the mob was moving toward one
of the country's four oil refineries in Kaduna.
</P>
<P>
Uneasy calm was reported Wednesday in Kaduna, capital of one of
Nigeria' s most important states, where the movement of people
have been restricted with troops patrolling the streets.
</P>
<P>
The soldiers and police had been given order to shoot any
troublemakers on sight. 
</P>
</TEXT>
