<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Highlights of S. Africa's New Fiscal Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, February 23 (Xinhua) -- The following is a brief
introduction of highlights of South Africa's new fiscal budget
2000/2001 unveiled by Finance Minister Trevor Manuel on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The budget includes a further relaxation of exchange controls,
setting the inflation targets at between three and six percent by
2002.
</P>
<P>
Value-added tax (VAT) and company tax rates are left unchanged,
but capital gains will be targeted from April 1, 2001.
</P>
<P>
A rise in excise duties will generate about 565 million rand
(89.6 million U.S. dollars) in 2000/2001.
</P>
<P>
The duty on a pack of cigarettes is raised by 38 cents while
tax on pipe tobacco is increased by 35 cents per 25 grams.
</P>
<P>
Beer drinkers would pay an additional two cents on a 340 ml
can, while a bottle of fortified wine goes up by six cents a
bottle. Spirits will cost 51 cents more a bottle, while the
excise duty on soft drinks was cut by four cents a litre.
</P>
<P>
The petrol levy will be up by five cents a litre, and diesel by
three cents from April 5.
</P>
<P>
Fishing and coastal shipping industries will receive a full
diesel rebate of the new general diesel fuel levy of 79.1 cents a
litre, the Road Accident Fund levy of 1.3 cents a litre, and the
Equalization Fund levy.
</P>
<P>
The Budget also contains a further relaxation of exchange
controls for companies.
</P>
<P>
Among the measures announced was a lifting of the asset swap
limit for unit trusts from 15 percent to 20 percent of total
assets under management.
</P>
<P>
Firms establishing or acquiring companies abroad will be
allowed to make use of assets swaps to finance foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
The current limit of 500,000 rand (79,365 U.S. dollars) for
private investments abroad would increase to 750,000 rand (119,000
U.S. dollars) per person.
</P>
<P>
The government hoped to generate five billion rand (7.93
billion U.S. dollars) from privatization.
</P>
<P>
The budget deficit for 1999/2000 was estimated at 2.4 percent
of GDP, revised down from 2.7 percent in last October.
</P>
<P>
The government would provide 272 million rand (43.2 million
U.S. dollars) to be used for teachers' professional development,
and social grants for old age, disability, war veterans and care
dependency would be hiked by 20 rand (3. 17 dollars) a month to
540 rand (86 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The police would receive an additional 1.1billion rand (174
million U.S. dollars) over the next two years, while justice will
be allocated an extra 470 million rand (74.6 million U.S.
dollars) over previous budget projections.
</P>
<P>
Poverty relief, infrastructure investment and the job creation
programs will be allocated 1.2 billion rand (190 million U.S.
dollars) in 2000/2001.
</P>
<P>
According to Manuel, the national economy is poised to grow
robustly at an average of 3.4 percent over the next three years.
The growth estimate for 2000 is 3.5 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000224.0345 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan's Woman Minister Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Deputy Prime Minister
and Minister of Planning Rima Khalaf, the only woman minister in
the cabinet of Prime Minister Abdel Rauf Rawabdeh, resigned
Wednesday over alleged personal reasons.
</P>
<P>
King Abdullah Bin Hussein, in a royal decree, accepted her
resignation, and appointed Minister of Trade, Industry and Supply
Mohammed Halayka concurrently as acting minister of planning.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's official news agency Petra carried a brief news
dispatch for Khalaf's resignation but did not give any reasons.
</P>
<P>
Answering questions from reporters, Minister of Information
Saleh Kallab said the woman minister resigned over personal
reasons.
</P>
<P>
Informed sources said Khalaf had tried but failed to extend the
service years of an employee in her ministry, who had exceeded the
retirement age of 60.
</P>
<P>
She was the third minister to resign in the 11-month-old
Rawabdeh government after former Minister of Youth and Sport
Mohammad Mamsar and former Minister of Transport Nasser Lawzi.
</P>
<P>
Mamsar resigned last July after failing to persuade Kuwait to
take part in the ninth Pan-Arab games held last August in Amman.
The Gulf emirate boycotted the games to protest against the
participation of Iraq which had invaded it during the 1990 Gulf
Crisis.
</P>
<P>
Lawzi gave up his portfolio of transport last December over
policy differences with Prime Minister Rawabdeh, whom he accused of
meddling too much in daily affairs of his ministry.
</P>
<P>
After Rawabdeh took office, his government has been under fire
from the public and opposition parties for a series of social,
economic and administrative reforms, including a measure to levy a
10 percent sale tax, which increased state revenues but triggered a
price hike in the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
However, he survived a major cabinet reshuffle in January when
seven ministers were asked by King Abdullah to leave their jobs.
</P>
<P>
Rawabdeh saved his post as the kingdom is emerging from a
decade-old economic recession since the Gulf Crisis, for which the
kingdom was isolated by Arab countries for its sympathy with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Jordan registered 1.5-2 percent economic growth in 1999, rare
and amazing since the Gulf Crisis.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
