<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil, Paraguay, to Tighten Bilateral Trade Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The Paraguayan and Brazilian
governments have agreed to exert tight controls on their bilateral
trade to eradicate smuggling in their border zone, official
sources said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Ministers of the two countries agreed this week on a plan of
action that includes a tighter control in Brazil on the
commodities being sent to Paraguay.
</P>
<P>
Both sides agreed to implement "integrated controls" in several
points of the border to make trade "transparent", added the same
sources.
</P>
<P>
The talks held here were about the double taxation to firms
interested in investing in Paraguay, corruption in the border
customs posts, and "money laundering," triangulation of
merchandise, "piracy," and commercial counterfeiting.
</P>
<P>
Brazilian Tax Minister Everardo Maciel told the Paraguayan
delegation that an agreement to give important tax incentives to
the Brazilian investors who want to reside in Paraguay is about to
be signed.
</P>
<P>
Paraguayan Communications and Public Works Minister Jose
Alberto Planas said that the National Development and Foreign
Trade of Brazil granted a 190 million dollar "tied credit" to
Paraguay.
</P>
<P>
This money will be used for the paving of important roads,
purchase of machinery for this ministry, equipment for the police,
two helicopters, patrol cars and ambulances. Also 80 million
dollars will be for the ministry and 22 million for the police.
</P>
<P>
The two neighboring countries are members of the Southern
Common Market (Mercosur), which also includes Argentine and
Uruguay. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
