<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuba Refuses to Recall Diplomat in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Cuban authorities rejected
Thursday the U.S. demand to recall no later than Saturday an
official of the island country charged with spying.
</P>
<P>
"Present your alleged evidence. Do not fear debate. You have
the possibility of rectifying and apologizing," said Cuban
Congress President Ricardo Alarcon.
</P>
<P>
Press reports identified the Cuban official as Jose Imperatori,
a member of the Cuban Interest Section in Washington.
</P>
<P>
"We have not recalled (the official), nor will we recall him,"
said Alarcon during the celebration of the 105th anniversary of
the second independence war of Cuba.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. State Department said that the Cuban diplomat has
until 13:30 local time Saturday to leave, or he will lose his
diplomatic immunity, and will be subjected to the U.S. laws, and
if there are reasons for his arrest, he will be detained.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service official Mariano
Faget was arrested in Miami under charges that he was spying for
Cuba and had links with Imperatori.
</P>
<P>
"It is about time for the United States to stand up and refuse
to be blackmailed" by the Cubans of Miami that oppose the
government of Fidel Castro," said Alarcon.
</P>
<P>
The president of the Cuban Parliament described Castro's foes
as "criminals without scruples" and annexist mafia."
</P>
<P>
Alarcon said that the Cuban government will insist in the
return to the island of boy Elian Gonzalez, survivor of the
wreckage in which his mother died last November and who was taken
to Miami.
</P>
<P>
He added that the government of Cuba will soon renew its demand
for the United States to withdraw from Guantanamo, in the eastern
tip o the island, where it has a military base. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
