<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swiss Government Pledges Continued Effort to Join United Nations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The Swiss government has
indicated it will go ahead with plans to join the United Nations,
even if a people's initiative on the issue fails to collect the
necessary 100,000 signatures.
</P>
<P>
After a special cabinet session on Thursday, the government
said that it had decided to launch a comprehensive consultation
process within Switzerland in order to present draft legislation
to parliament by the end of the year, according to Swiss Radio
International.
</P>
<P>
UN membership for Switzerland was massively turned down by
voters in 1986. Since 1998 a pro-UN committee has been collecting
signatures to try to force another national referendum on the
subject.
</P>
<P>
Joining the world body has been an objective of the Swiss
government for many years, but until recently the cabinet has been
wary about debating the subject in the light of the over 70 per
cent of voters who said no in 1986.
</P>
<P>
Opponents argue that the considerable Swiss annual contribution
is enough and that there is no need to get more involved with the
world body. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
