<DOCNO> XIE20000224.0353 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Finance Minister on Debt Cancellation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government Thursday
 reaffirmed the need for the country to be considered under the
Highly Indebted Poor Countries (HIPC) so that it can benefit from
its debtors.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Katele Kalumba said here that the government
is doing everything possible to meet the International Monetary
Fund (IMF) laid down benchmarks so that Zambia could be considered
for the HIPC by July this year.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Jubilee 2000-debt cancellation conference held
here Thursday, Kalumba said that the Zambian government has been
forced to change the law in order to meet the benchmark of selling
the Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines (ZCCM).
</P>
<P>
He told the participants drawn from various local and
international organizations that apart from ensuring the speedy
disposal of the ZCCM, the government is striving to ensure good
governance, gender equality, transparency prevailed in the country
in order for it to join the HIPC.
</P>
<P>
Under HIPC, Zambia stands to benefit through the cancellation
of up to 90 percent of its 6.5 billion U.S. dollar debt it owes
both the Paris Club and its multilateral creditors.
</P>
<P>
Acting Director of the External Resources Management at the
Ministry of Finance and Economical Development, Patrick Malambo,
also delivered a speech at the conference.
</P>
<P>
He said that although one of the benefits for the countries to
join the HIPC is the cancellation of debts of up to 90 percent,
Zambia's cancellation will only amount to 2.5 billion U.S. dollars
accumulated before 1983, when it graduates to the HIPC program
sometime this year.
</P>
<P>
Malambo emphasized Zambia's fulfilment of the International
Monetary fund (IMF) set benchmarks, which include the speedy and
complete sale of the mining giant, ZCCM.
</P>
<P>
He also revealed that Zambia had defaulted in the past in its
debt services due to poor government debt management, but now the
situation has improved and there would be a more constant approach
to debt management. 
</P>
</TEXT>
