<HEADLINE> Europe Invests in L.America More than US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VILAMOURA, Portugal, February 24 (Xinhua) -- European
Commissioner for Foreign Relations Chris Patten said here Thursday
that there are more European than United States' investment in
Latin America
</P>
<P>
Patten quoted a document recently published by the United
Nations that the growing investments of European firms in Latin
America last year surpass those of the United States, which used
to be the main investors in that zone.
</P>
<P>
"This reflects a growing confidence of Europe in the political
and economic changes in that region," said the European official,
stating the idea that Latin Americas is in reality one of the
European Union priorities.
</P>
<P>
"I want to underscore that the development of the relations
between the two parts is a true priority for the European Union,
now and in the coming years," said Patten.
</P>
<P>
Paten said of the meeting being held this week here between the
representatives of the European Union, the San Jose Group, the
Andean Community, Mercosur, and the Group of Rio, that he has big
expectations about the launching of the negotiations between the
European Union and Mercosur.
</P>
<P>
The representatives of the European Union and Southern Common
Market (Mercosur),  agreed Wednesday to start talks about a free
trade agreement that includes aspects of political, technical,
commercial, and economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Officials also announced that negotiators from the EU and the
Mercosur will meet for the first time in April in Buenos Aires and
Santiago de Chile.
</P>
<P>
The Mercosur includes Latin America's strongest economic
performers: Argentine, Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay and also Chile
and Bolivia as associate members.
</P>
<P>
Free trade will enrich the Europeans by 6 billion dollars a
year and the Mercosur side by 5 billion dollars, according to EU.
</P>
<P>
EU exports to Latin America stand at about 52.4 billion dollars,
well above EU imports of 38.1 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Economic sources said the EU is eager to expand trade with
Latin America, fearing it could lose ground to the United States,
which is seeking to crate a Pan-American free-trade area by 2005.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
