<HEADLINE> Blue Chips Fall Sharply But Tech Shares Hit New High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, February 24 (Xinhua) -- Blue chips stocks on Wall
Street fell sharply on fears of higher interest rates Thursday but
the technology shares hit the new high.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed down 133.10 at 10,092.
63, after dropping briefly below 10,000 in earlier trading. The
index is now down 14 percent from its record closing high of 11,
722.98 on January 14.
</P>
<P>
At midafternoon today, the Dow fell as much as 233.00 at 9,992.
73. The index fell below 10,000 on April 6, after finishing above
the 10,000 milestone for the first time on March 29, 1999 and it
traded below the five digital again on October 18.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index also fell 7.26 at 1,353.43.
</P>
<P>
The Dow index continued to plunge the day after the Federal
Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan repeated his warning of higher
rates. In an appearance before the Senate Banking Committee
Wednesday, Greenspan said while he was not aiming at stock prices,
he had to be concerned about how the run-up on Wall Street
translated into more consumer spending and a broader increase in
demand for goods and services. His comments pushed the Dow index
79.11 points lower that day.
</P>
<P>
But the technology stocks rose 67.32 at 4,617.65 today in
defiance of Greenspan's warning for the second day in a row. The
index surpassed the record closing high of 4550.33 points set
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Reserve has raised interest rates four times since
June, last year in an effort to cool off the U.S. economy. But
Greenspan told the House Banking Committee last week that those
increases have had little impact.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index fell 5.06 at 583.57. But the American Stock
Exchange index rose 0.63 at 935.62 and the Russell 2000 index of
smaller companies rose 4.13 at 554.04.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 2-to-1 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 2,014 down, 1,049 up and 442
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume increased to 1.16 billion shares from 975.50
million in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
