<HEADLINE> Clinton Signs Directive on Foreign Police Training </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said the 10-million-U.S.-
dollars program would improve U.S. capacity to provide police
overseas in coordination with the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
"The president's decision is aimed at two related goals. The
first is to improve coordination of U.S. efforts. The second is
to enhance the ability of other countries, the U.N. and regional
organizations to plan, mount and sustain operations in support of
the rule of law," Albright told a press conference on the
directive.
</P>
<P>
She added that the province of Kosovo in Serbia, East Timor and
Sierra Leone were places where trained civilian police were needed.
</P>
<P>
Clinton has instructed the State Department to create a leading
office responsible for issues associated with our participation in
the criminal justice component of peace operations, Albright said.
</P>
<P>
The office will be responsible for developing policy, setting
priorities and coordinating U.S. agency activities.
</P>
<P>
"This step recognizes the foreign-policy importance of
preventing security vacuums from arising in post-conflict
situations," she added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
