<DOCNO> XIE20000224.0361 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate Passes New Sanctions Bill Against Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Senate,
contrasting the Clinton administration's gesture to improve
relations with Iran through unconditional dialogue, Thursday
approved a bill aimed at stepping up sanctions against Teheran,
saying it would require the president to step up efforts to stop
Russia and other countries from supplying so-called weapons of
mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
The Senate voted 98-0 to pass the bill, which was based on a
bill approved 419-0 in the House of Representatives last September
with a slightly different version. And the House is expected to
adopt the Senate revised bill and sent it to the president.
</P>
<P>
The White House threatened to veto the bill once the House
adopts, saying it complicated international nonproliferation
efforts.
</P>
<P>
The bill contrasted the administration's effort to improve
relations with Iran.
</P>
<P>
The State Department Tuesday made a gesture for unconditional
dialogue with Iran after a newly elected Iranian parliament is
prepared to hold its first session. Spokesman James Rubin welcomed
the result of the Iranian parliamentary election last Friday,
hoping the newly elected reformist members of parliament would
lead the country to rapprochement between the two nations after
more the 20 years of hostility.
</P>
<P>
The Senate bill directs the president to submit reports to
Congress every six months identifying foreign persons or countries
that transfer weapons material or technology to Iran and
authorizes him to impose sanction if he so chooses.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, Congress approved a bill that required the president
to impose sanction against Russia and others that supply missiles
or weapons to Iran. The bill was vetoed by President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's Senate bill makes some changes and just asks the
president to impose sanctions on countries he chooses.
</P>
<P>
After the 1998 veto, the administration moved on its own to
announce sanctions on seven Russian entities suspected of
transferring weapons technology to Iran. In 1999, three more
Russian groups were added to the list.
</P>
<P>
But Senate Majority leader Trent Lott said this had not done
enough to stop the flow of weapons technology. He said that with
enactment of the bill, "we hope the administration will use it to
our country's advantage and impose sanctions." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
