<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Indicates It May Send More Troops to Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Speaking to reporters at the State Department, Albright said
the U.S. is "obviously very pleased" that France decided to
augment their forces in Mitrovica, where the civilians clashed
with the peace-keeping troops.
</P>
<P>
"I think that clearly the situation in Mitrovica poses a
challenge for us, and it's very important for KFOR to make clear
that it is in charge, because it deters violence, and it sends a
very strong message," Albright told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The United States currently has about 5,700 troops in Kosovo. "
The United States has the largest number of troops in the area, so
we do believe -- or in Kosovo as a whole -- that we are definitely
doing our part," Albright said.
</P>
<P>
"But I don't exclude the fact that there may have to be some
Americans, and -- but I think, in the first instance, we are
looking to others to plus-up their forces," she added.
</P>
<P>
French Defense Minister Alain Richard announced Wednesday after
meeting U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen that France is
deploying about 600 to 700 troops to the area it controlled in
Kosovo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
