<HEADLINE> Antidrug Regional Strategy Sought in Costa Rica </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The meeting is sponsored by the legislative assemblies of the
five Central American countries -- Costa Rica, Nicaragua, Honduras,
El Salvador, and Guatemala -- besides Panama and Belize, with the
goal of proposing two treaties, one to fight corruption, and the
other to combat drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
It is planned with the second one to extend to all Central
America a treaty of joint patrolling between the countries of the
region and the United States, similar to the one in force with
Costa Rica.
</P>
<P>
U.S. South Command sub-head General Alfred Valenzuela tried to
show in the middle of graphs and maps how the drug produced in
South America, especially in Colombia, travels by Central America,
the Caribbean, and the Pacific, toward the consumers markets,
especially the United States.
</P>
<P>
Valenzuela presented figures according to which almost 15,000
young U.S. citizens lost their lives in 1998 because of drug
overdoses, saying that there are 14 million consumers of illicit
drugs in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Three hundred tons of the 500 metric tons of the estimated
production of cocaine in Colombia in 1998 went to the U.S. market,
said Valenzuela, adding that the production of the South American
country has increased .
</P>
<P>
The U.S. army wants to reinforce its participation in the war
against drugs through logistic support, with planes and
helicopters, as well as with information, operating from regional
bases, like the one it has in Honduras.
</P>
<P>
Colombia has proposed a plan to combat drug traffic that has a
cost of 7 billion dollars, of which 3.5 billion would have to come
from abroad.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton has proposed the Congress of his
country to support that plan with 1.6 billion dollars, which has
not been approved yet.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. strategy is clearly directed to reinforce its presence
in the region, to establish here its bases of operation that will
be used to combat drug traffic, but that will also operate with
more facilities after having surrendered last December the
military installations it had in Panama.
</P>
<P>
The United States Army Southern Command itself, which during
decades had its base in the Panama Canal Zone, had to be installed
in Miami, so the U.S. government still seeks facilities to operate
in Central America. 
</P>
