<HEADLINE> US Drug Czar Ends Colombia Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, February 24 (Xinhua) -- U.S. drug czar
Barry McCaffrey ended Thursday his visit to Colombia with a trip
to the modern installations of the army against drug trafficking
in the southern jungles.
</P>
<P>
Colombian Armed Forces Commander General Fernando Tapias and
other high ranking officials accompanied MacCaffrey in this trip.
The U.S. drug czar arrived Tuesday to fine-tune with President
Andres Pastrana the details of an economic assistance.
</P>
<P>
These resources will be used to eradicate illegal crops in this
Andean country and the new antidrug campaign will be launched from
the Tres Esquinas Base, located in the limits between the El
Caqueta and the Putumayo departments.
</P>
<P>
The so-called Joint Intelligence Central for the control of drug
trafficking in the Colombian southern jungles was bilaterally
established a few weeks ago in this base.
</P>
<P>
McCaffrey's visit to the South American country comes as U.S.
Congress debates the Clinton administration's proposed 1.6 billion
dollar counternarcotics package for Colombia and its Andean
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
It was estimated that cocaine production increased by 20
percent and heroin production up 23 percent last year in Colombia.
U.S. officials say the South American country now supplies 90
percent of the world's cocaine and the majority of the heroin sold
in the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
