<HEADLINE> U.S. Criticizes Levy's Threat on Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 24 (Xinhua) -- the United States, fearing
to derail peace process in the Middle East, on Thursday criticized
Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy for his threat to "burn" the
soil of Lebanon if Hezbollah guerrillas attacked the north of his
country.
</P>
<P>
"This kind of comment is inappropriate. We don't need rhetoric
from anybody that inflames the situation," State Department
spokesman James Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
"What we want to do is to create a climate where tensions are
diffused. Such comments make our efforts extremely difficult," he
added.
</P>
<P>
It was the strongest criticism on Israel from the Clinton
administration since violence erupted over past weeks between
Israel and Hezbollah in southern Lebanon. The United States has
also criticized Israeli attacks on civilian infrastructure in
Lebanon, but only after violent protests at the U.S. embassy in
Beirut.
</P>
<P>
Levy Israel's parliament on Wednesday that Israel would
retaliate "blood by blood, soul for soul, child for child" if
Hezbollah fired rockets at Kiryat Shmona and other communities in
northern Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
