<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sinn Fein Leader Says All N. Irish Parties Be Disarmed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Speaking at the National Press Club, McGuinness said that the
pro-Britain Unionists Party, which has 150,000 weapons at its
disposal, should also be disarmed, not only the Irish Republic
Army (IRA).
</P>
<P>
He also expressed his irritation at the charges that IRA's
refusal to start decommissioning is the cause of recent setbacks
to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
"The peace process is in deep crisis, and it's in deep crisis
for one reason only: the action of Peter Mandelson in suspending
the power-sharing government established under the Good Friday
agreement," McGuinness said.
</P>
<P>
Parties involved in the conflict in Northern Ireland signed the
Good Friday Accords in 1998 but still disagree on the
implementation of the accords.
</P>
<P>
Mandelson, British secretary for the Northern Ireland affairs,
announced earlier this month suspension of the self-rule coalition
government in the province, citing reasons that IRA, a
paramilitary group under Sinn Fein, failed to begin
decommissioning.
</P>
<P>
"The Good Friday agreement was not implemented in one of its
most vital areas: the setting up of a power-sharing government.
The unionists blocked that government for 19 months of those two
years," McGuinness said.
</P>
<P>
He accused Mandelson of bearing much of the responsibility for
the setbacks though his decision to dissolve the local government
despite Sinn Fein's having brought forth "a new and significant
proposal."
</P>
<P>
"What the British have done is totally and absolutely illegal,"
McGuinness said.
</P>
<P>
McGuinness told reporters that the Good Friday Accords, which
established the basis for peace in the province, assert that it is
the "collective responsibility" of all participants to work
cooperatively to achieve decommissioning, or disarmament.
</P>
<P>
"It (the agreement) does not guarantee that decommissioning
will occur within two years. It requires that the political
parties, Sinn Fein included, use good-faith efforts to have it
occur. Nobody except the unionists is challenging Sinn Fein's
good-faith efforts," he added.
</P>
<P>
"People think that the only guns that are causing problems are
the guns of the IRA," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We in Sinn Fein also have concerns about guns," he said,
referring to the weapons held by the Unionists and the British
troops deployed in the province.
</P>
<P>
McGuinness served as education secretary of the local
government in Northern Ireland that was suspended by the British
government two weeks ago because of the disarmament issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
