<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: United Nations Takes A Critical Step Forward in Ending  DRC Conflict  (by Gu Zhenqiu) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, February 24 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security
Council Thursday unanimously gave a green light to the deployment
of 5,500 peace-keepers in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC)
in order to monitor the Central African nation's shaky peace
process in what has been described as Africa's first world war.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council, which has the primary responsibility for
the maintenance of world peace and security, voted 15-0 to adopt a
resolution in what has been seen as a gesture to heed the repeated
and collective appeals from the international community, including
African regional leaders in particular, to send peace-keepers into
the war-torn DRC at an early date.
</P>
<P>
The resolution, adopted after weeks of negotiations, spelt out
conditions for the U.N. military deployment -- the respect for the
Lusaka Cease-fire Agreement, the preparation of the disengagement
of forces and the guarantee of security and the freedom of
movement for U.N. personnel.
</P>
<P>
The resolution demonstrates the readiness and determination of
the international community, including the Security Council, to
offer a hand in promoting the peace process in the country, which,
formerly known as Zaire, is located in "the heart of Africa."
</P>
<P>
It is widely accepted that the DRC conflict, which has drawn
six African countries, is a highly complicated and sensitive issue.
The U.N. deployment, if completed, is designed only to assist the
implementation of part of the Lusaka Cease-fire Agreement, signed
by warring parties on July 10 last year in Zambia.
</P>
<P>
While the further deployment of forces is a good step, more
and harder tasks are laying before the world community and the
parties to the conflict, which called for concerted efforts.
</P>
<P>
First, the full respect of the sovereignty and territorial
integrity, and the strict adherence to the Lusaka Agreement
constitute the sound basis for the political settlement of the
current crisis in DRC.
</P>
<P>
Repeated violations of the cease-fire by almost all parties
has stalled one of the agreement's most vital aspects: the
deployment of U.N. peace-keepers in the African nation.
</P>
<P>
The United States, which sponsored the resolution and financed
about 30 percent of the U.N. peace-keeping operations in DRC,
refuses to bring in peace-keepers until there are improved
security guarantees.
</P>
<P>
Second, it is highly imperative for all warring parties to
engage in unconditional cooperation to end the many-sided war in
DRC despite their deep distrust and profound hatred.
</P>
<P>
The cooperation, a must among warring parties and between the
U.N. peace-keepers and the warring factions, can create a required
atmosphere conducive to the implementation of Lusaka Agreement,
which includes the orderly withdrawal of all foreign troops from
the DRC soil, as is demanded by the U.N. resolution.
</P>
<P>
Aside from its international ramifications, the conflict in
DRC has triggered a human rights catastrophe. According to a
recent U.N. assessment, DRC is host to 960,000 refugees from nine
neighboring countries. Overall, some 12.7 million people -- or 21
percent of the population -- face varying levels of food
insecurity.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, any delay in the long-awaited cooperation among
warring parties will create further crisis in the country.
</P>
<P>
Third, it is also crucial that an open, inclusive and
democratic national dialogue on the future of DRC get under way as
soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
For DRC, the Lusaka Agreement has established a process of
dialogue that African leaders hope will lead to national
reconciliation in the country. They recently appointed a
facilitator, Ketumile Masire, to achieve this end. But as Masire
pointed out, the outcome of his efforts relies on the willingness
of the Congolese people to reconcile.
</P>
<P>
In short, the Security Council has taken a critical step to
help DRC to come to a peace that its people so desperately need.
However, the situation on the ground is so complicated that it
would not only be naive but dangerous to rely on its settlement by
external forces.
</P>
<P>
The DRC conflict broke out in August 1998 when rebels, backed
by Uganda and Rwanda, launched an offensive to oust President
Laurent Kabila. It has soaked up fighting forces from at least six
African countries -- with troops from Zimbabwe, Namibia and Angola
all fighting on Kabila's side.
</P>
<P>
Welcoming development took place. The Security Council adopted
the resolution well after the end of a one-day special summit in
Lusaka, which attracted seven African regional leaders, including
those from DRC and other countries involved in the 16-month
conflict.
</P>
<P>
The summit concluded with a joint communique which reaffirmed
the African leaders' strong commitment to the Lusaka accord and
reiterated their determination for its full implementation.
Acknowledging that some violations of the agreement have occurred,
the summit undertook to ensure that such violations are addressed
promptly through the established mechanisms.
</P>
<P>
For now, the immediate challenge in DRC is for the warring
parties to mellow down their hostile propaganda and create an
atmosphere conducive for the Lusaka accord to be carried out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
